<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- Some 40 percent of South Korean companies are planning
to cut their manpower due to the current financial crisis, said a
survey issued by the Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Tuesday. (S. Korea-Cut Labor Force)
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Chechen kidnapers reportedly demanded a ransom of 3
million U.S. dollars for the release of five Polish aid workers
held hostage since December 17.
</P>
<P>
Media reports published here Tuesday said the ransom demand was
confirmed by Mohamed Mohamedov, deputy chief of the anti-terrorist
center in Chechnya, a republic of Russia.(Poland-Chechen Kidnapers)
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous country
which is struggling to overcome a monetary crisis, Tuesday
announced a balanced budget for the 1998/99 fiscal year (April
1-March 31).(India-Budget)
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- As many as 1,249 people were killed and 16,000 others
wounded in road accidents on two highways in Bangladesh in 1997,
reports said Tuesday. (Bangladesh-Road Accidents)
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- More than 160 people were massacred over the past two
days in western Algeria by Islamic militants, adding the number of
people killed since the beginning of Ramadan to more than 500,
reports from Algeria said. (Algeria-Massacre)
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has postponed his
India visit, scheduled to begin on January 19, to later this year,
a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Tuesday. (India-Yeltsin-Visit)
</P>
</TEXT>
