<HEADLINE> UK Medium-Sized Firms Plagued By Shortage of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Half of firms in the
mid-corporate market in Britain are finding it difficult to
recruit skilled workers, according to a survey released on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This situation is fueling fears that the profits of
medium-sized firms will suffer a severe downturn this year.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on a sample of 2000 firms, shows that they
are already in the throes of the biggest profits squeeze since the
last recession.
</P>
<P>
One in five firms is being forced to cut prices to compete
against cheap foreign imports and domestic rivals.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly acknowledged here that the skills shortage will
erode profits further as businesses are forced to pay higher wages
to attract competent staff.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a quarter of medium-sized businesses took on new workers
over the past six months, the largest rise for five years.
</P>
<P>
Employment agencies say the biggest shortages are in
computer-literate office staff, electronics and telecommunications
workers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported almost half of firms in Britain are now
operating at full capacity, the highest since the survey began in
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
