<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Calls for Stronger British-Zambian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
today spoke highly of Britain's continued assistance to Zambia
and called for stronger Anglo-Zambian ties, the Zambia News
Agency ZANA reported.
</P>
<P>
Receiving in the State House credentials from Thomas Young,
new British high commissioner to Zambia, Chiluba noted that
Zambia has been receiving British support in the balance of
payment and other economic spheres.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that his government will continue working together
with its British counterpart to realize sustainable development
in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Strong economic foundation has been set up in Zambia, Chiluba
noted, without which real development for the nation is
impossible.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program is on its course, said the
president, adding that the government will continue with the
process of dialogue with the opposition parties as part of the
country's democratic process.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the meeting, Young, the British high commissioner
said that the British government attaches great importance to the
close and warm relations existing between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged ties of brotherhood and the common understanding
should be used for the benefit of Africa and the world at large,
Young added.
</P>
<P>
The British envoy stressed Britain's respects for Zambia's
rule of law and sovereignty in line with the United Nations
Charter.
</P>
<P>
This is an apparent response to the recent strong accusations
made by the Zambian government that Britain and the U.S. as well
as some other countries are interfering with Zambia's internal
affairs concerning the continued detention of former president
Kenneth Kaunda, who is allegedly connected with the country's
abortive military coup last October.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. expressed deep concern after Kaunda was
arrested last December and asked the Zambian government either to
release him or to charge him immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
