<HEADLINE> Millennium Bug Threatens Firms' Bank Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Banks may call in up to 19.2
billion U.S. dollars of loans from small firms that fail to
prepare for the millennium computer bug, said British business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
More than a million companies, a quarter of the small business
community, could find lending facilities withdrawn or curtailed,
according to the Federation of Small Businesses.
</P>
<P>
The British government last week urged small businesses to take
measures to the millennium bug. It sets to head a taskforce to
alert firms to the dangers.
</P>
<P>
A research by leading factoring company Alex Lawrie shows that
more than 80 per cent of small businesses have done nothing to
prepare.
</P>
<P>
The bug is a threat because many computers cannot recognize the
digits 00 as the start of a new century. Experts believe it will
send systems haywire.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Alambritis of the Federation of Small Businesses
estimates that unless firms are ready for 2000 by the end of this
year, in 1999 the banks may withdraw up to a third of the 56
billion U.S. dollars of loans outstanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
