<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Irish Protestant Extremists Refuse to Back Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Protestant
leaders held an emergence meeting with jailed pro-British
extremists in Northern Ireland today but failed to get their
support for the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said the inmates of Ulster Defense Association
(UDA) and Ulster Freedom Fighters (UFF) in the Maze prison refused
at the meeting to back the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Gary McMichael, leader of the Ulster Democratic Party (UDP),
the loyalist guerrilla groups' political arm, said after the talks
that he wanted the peace process to continue and talks with UFF
leaders were planned.
</P>
<P>
"We owe a responsibility to try and ensure that there remains
to be a commitment to this process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Loyalist sources said the prisoners' decision is not a signal
that they want the ceasefire to end, but politicians regard it as
a worrying development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam held a second
day of separate meetings with major political parties in the
province, including Sinn Fein, the political arm of the outlawed
Irish Republican Army (IRA), and the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP),
chief advocate of British rule.
</P>
<P>
She said rival political parties do not want a return to the
dark days of sectarian warfare and are determined to make progress
in the round-table talks due to resume next week.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, responding to the Unionists's
refusal to talks with anti-British republicans, said the Unionists
are trying to assert a veto in the Northern Ireland peace talks
and have left a vacuum filled by loyalist killings.
</P>
<P>
Tension has risen in the British-ruled province after a
guerrilla flare-up claimed three lives in a week and plunged hopes
of an early political agreement into gloom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
