<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Grow Up 2.5 pct in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. factory orders went
up a 2.5 percent in November, mainly due to demand for commercial
aircraft and parts, the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The gain to a seasonally adjusted 345.1 billion U.S. dollars,
the sixth consecutive monthly growth, was the largest in 14
months, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders alone shot up 21 percent, almost entirely
due to demand for aircraft and parts. It was the largest growth
since July 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, excluding the transportation sector, orders fell 0.3
percent in November, the second decline in a row.
</P>
<P>
In November, orders for durable goods, expensive items which
could be used for more than three years, from aircraft to steel
girders, rose 4.8 percent. It was the fifth increase in six
months.
</P>
<P>
Orders for primary metals such as steel and electronic and
electrical equipment also rose. But orders declined for industrial
machinery, stone clay and glass products and fabricated metal
products.
</P>
<P>
Orders for non-durable goods fell 0.3 percent in the first drop
since August. Petroleum and chemical products also decreased,
offsetting an increase in food products.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of factory goods, a measure of current production,
fell 0.3 percent in November, partly blaming for the Asian crisis.
The backlog of unfilled orders jumped 2.3 percent, the sixth
increase in seven months. Manufacturing inventories, up 16 of the
last 17 months, increased 0.4 percent in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
