<HEADLINE> U.S. Automakers Complete for Gas-Saving Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. car makers are completing
for energy saving vehicles, which may kindle a revolutionary
change in engine technology.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Corp., the country's No. 3 automaker, unveiled plans
today to make its popular sports vehicles as fuel-efficient as
cars.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp. said Sunday and Ford announced Monday that
they would be ready to produce a hybrid-electric vehicles by 2001
and fuel cell cars by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the industry is locked in a brutal race to
develop the technology to replace the internal-combustion engine.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler will reduce the polluting emissions in its Jeep
Wranglers, Cherokees and Grand Cherokees beginning with the 1999
model year, it is reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The company is also developing a hybrid car that would run 70
miles per gallon, cost the same as a conventional car and be ready
for production as early as 2003.
</P>
<P>
The hybrid car uses a small battery to power the car's
accessories and boost the engine during hard acceleration, but
otherwise runs on a diesel engine.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Motor Corp.'s Prius hybrid electric-and-gasoline car,
which gets an estimated 66 miles a gallon and went on sale in
Japan last month.
</P>
<P>
The changes in the auto industry will also affect many
industries, according to analysts. So-called energy stations will
replace many gasoline stations. They are also pushing the oil
industry to cut the sulfur content of gasoline in the U.S. to help
them further reduce vehicle emissions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
