<HEADLINE> Spain to Become S. Africa's Major Trade Partner: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Spain is gearing to become
one of the South Africa's biggest economic partners in Europe,
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted a Spanish diplomat
as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
"Spain has the determination and capacity to increase its
economic relations with South Africa in numerous fields, such as
the automotive industry, energy, tourism, defense, transfer of
technology and last but not least, the fishing industry," Spanish
ambassador Miguel Carriedo was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Spain is trying to win the South African defense tender valued
at more than 7.5 billion Rand (1.6 billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Trade with South Africa currently accounts for only one
percent of Spanish exports and two percent of imports. There are
no bilateral investments of importance.
</P>
<P>
Spanish fishing experts visited South Africa in November last
year on a fact-finding tour of the local fishing industry. The
information would be evaluated following which an agreement of
cooperation would be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would include technical and financial assistance
regarding fishing techniques, ship building, international
marketing, processing and freezing techniques and the
construction of fish processing plants valued at more than 61
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Spain had initiated a 35 million Rand (7.1 million U.S.
Dollars) project aimed at developing the South African tourism
industry into one of the country's major foreign exchanges
earners and job providers, Spanish counsellor to South Africa Jos
Pasqual Marco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
