<HEADLINE> Annan Approves Iraqi Food Distribution Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan had approved Iraq's distribution plan of food, medicine and
other humanitarian supplies on Monday night, the Office of the
Spokesman for the Secretary-General announced today.
</P>
<P>
The distribution plan for phase three under the oil-for-food
program was approved last night, and the Secretary-General
had informed the president of the Security Council as well as
the Iraqi Government about the approval, the spokesman's office
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq, which has been under UN
economic sanctions since it invaded Kuwait in 1990, is allowed to
sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy
necessities for its people.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, first implemented in December, 1996, was
renewed last month for the third time. But Iraq said it would
not export any oil until the UN chief approved the food
distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rasheed said on Tuesday in
Baghdad that Iraq would export oil under its oil-for-food deal
with the United Nations two days after approval of the
distribution plan by the UN Secretary-General. 
</P>
</TEXT>
