<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Changes Force Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Another Nigerian general has been
named as force commander of the west African peace-keeping force
known as ECOMOG to replace Major-General Victor Malu.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Major-General Timothy Shelpidi, the defense
Chief of Training, Operations and Plans (CTOP) in Nigeria, will
take effect this Thursday, according to the defense headquarters
today.
</P>
<P>
Malu, who will soon return from Liberia, has been equally
appointed as the general officer commanding (GOC) 2 mechanized
division of the Nigerian army stationed in Ibadan, one of the
biggest cities in the west.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi was a principal staff officer in the presidency
between 1990 and 1993. He was also a GOC 82 division of the
Nigerian army before he became CTOP, reportedly the number two
person in the defense headquarters, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new CTOP has not been named, neither did the authorities
make known the appointment of the ECOMOG chief.
</P>
<P>
However, defense spokesman Col. Godwin Ugbo described the
appointment as "purely military affair" when asked about whether
it had anything to do with the apparent cold relations between
Malu and Liberian President Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
The two men reportedly disagreed on whether ECOMOG would
involve in the restructuring of Liberia's post-war armed forces
as mandated by the 1996 Abuja peace accord, which brought an end
to the country's seven-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Liberian government has begun
preparations for the restructuring by itself, although the ECOMOG
operations in that country has not been "dismantled" by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) high command.
</P>
<P>
As the first step of a phased pullout plan, 1,205 ECOMOG
officers and soldiers had been pulled out of Monrovia two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
Reports said some of them have been redeployed to Sierra Leone
to join in the full operation there.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now still has six battalions in Liberia whereas Ghana
has two, he said, adding, "when the orders come to move finally,
we will move."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
