<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Dollar to Slide Further: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Dollar which
depreciated 23 percent last year will fall further by an
estimated 20 percent this year, economic commentators predicted
today.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the Dollar which plunged to an all time low
last year against major currencies under immense pressure from
high import demand would remain under the same pressure this
year.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. Dollar equals to 17 Zimbabwe Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Andy Hodges, money market analyst from the Commercial Bank,
said the local currency is likely to fall by between 19 and 20
percent by April and even further by between 22 and 23 percent at
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
As long as the import-export imbalance continued, he said, it
would drop further.
</P>
<P>
"If we keep on importing more than we export, then we will
always have a high demand for foreign currency, putting pressure
on the Zimbabwe Dollar," Hodges noted.
</P>
<P>
John Makamure, an economist from the Zimbabwe National Chamber
of Commerce, blamed the slide of the local Dollar on the
country's declining exports.
</P>
<P>
"The Dollar will continue under pressure because our export
sector is weak which means our inflows of foreign exchange are
less than the outflows," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Makamure added that fears of an El-Nino-induced drought would
further worsen the situation as the government might be forced to
import food.
</P>
<P>
The recent release by the World Bank of one billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (60 million U.S. Dollars) to the Zimbabwe government for
balance of payments support would only stabilize the exchange
rate in the short term, since the export sector remained weak, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank Zimbabwe said in its latest economic
bulletin that "with the need to revise the mini-budget, resumed
donor funding would appear to be off the agenda until the second
quarter of 1998. Accordingly, during 1998 the Zimbabwe Dollar is
likely to depreciate a further 20 percent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Unveils Budget for 1998/99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
Tuesday evening announced a balanced budget for the fiscal year
1998/99 starting on April 1, targeting higher oil revenues,
non-oil exports and increased development aid.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised address to the House of People's
Representatives, Soeharto submitted a 133.49 trillion rupiah
(about 33.37 billion U.S. dollars at the conversion rate of 4,000
per dollar) draft budget, a 32.1 percent increase over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which is expected to be passed into law by
legislators, forecasts domestic revenues to reach 107.688 trillion
rupiah, an increase of 22.3 percent. Development revenues are
expected to reach 25.804 trillion rupiah (includes 6.8 trillion
rupiah for program aid and 19.004 trillion rupiah for project
aid), a rise of 98.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas revenues are forecast to climb sharply to 27.286
trillion rupiah, a growth of 83.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Revenues from non-oil and gas are expected to increase by 9.9
percent to 80.402 trillion rupiah with the largest source coming
from income tax and value added tax of 54.167 trillion rupiah, an
increase of 11.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia's economic growth dropped to 5.1 percent in
1997 from the previous year's 7.98 percent as a result of the
prolonged monetary crisis and natural disasters which badly hit
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian currency rupiah has lost more than 100 percent
of its value against the U.S. dollar since July last year and many
small and medium-sized firms have closed down because of the
government's tight monetary policies and banks' higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, Indonesia's economy will grow by four percent
during 1998-99. "It is a very low figure, compared to our annual
economic growth during the last 30 years, that reached an average
of around 7 percent," Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inflation rate, which had been declining since
1993, rose to 11.05 percent in 1997 compared with 6.47 percent in
1996. The main cause was a 6.28 percent rise in foodstuffs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the higher inflation rate and monetary crisis,
with all its consequences, will continue to persist in 1998, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the monetary turmoil, the president said the draft state
budget is designed to overcome the crisis and that the private
sector should follow government efforts to limit expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The private sector and the government should examine and
correct themselves, he said, adding that they should be wise in
choosing which projects should be given priority and which should
be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto pledged to continue the economic reform program,
including financial reforms and restructuring covering the
monetary sector, banking, fiscal issues, domestic and foreign
trade, investment and the privatization of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said the poverty eradication program should still be
given priority.
</P>
<P>
"(In the draft budget) the amount for poverty eradication is
two-thirds of government savings," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he added, foreign loans will be used to accelerate
rural development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
