<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Land Issue, Concern to UK: British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A visiting British Minister
today said he will discuss Zimbabwe's land issue when meeting
Zimbabwe's acting President Simon Mudenda at their scheduled
meeting tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
British Minister of State at the Foreign and Commonwealth
Office Tony Lloyd made the remarks when arriving in Harare today
as the first minister in the new British Labor government to
visit Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd said Britain could only support Zimbabwe's resettlement
program if schemes were designed to help the poorest people in
the country.
</P>
<P>
He comes to Zimbabwe at a time when the Zimbabwe government
has released the list of over 1,500 commercial farms targeted for
compulsory acquisition under which compensation would only be
for developments made and not for the land itself.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, currently on holiday in
Europe, has said Britain should provide the money for land
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd said that his government is concerned that Zimbabwe's
latest plans on the land issue might not best benefit the
landless poor.
</P>
<P>
''We can only supportean the land scheme to help people living
in poverty,'' Lloyd said, adding, ''what we can't help is the
scheme as it is now. We are concerned that the present plan will
not solve the problems of the poor landless people in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
He was speaking soon after meeting over 400 squatters at Porta
farm, 40 km west of Harare.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd will discuss other bilateral issues with Muzenda after
which he will hold a press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
