<HEADLINE> Nigeria, US Airlink May be Restored Soon: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi has raised hopes of restoring airlink with the United
States, which was severed 54 months ago by the U.S. for alleged
security lapses at the Lagos International Airport.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out the settlement of the aviation dispute with
Britain for now until the latter recognizes Nigeria's
independence and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi was quoted by local press as saying on Monday that high
level diplomatic discussion between Nigeria and the U.S. was in
progress to fine-tune areas of disagreement between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
The minister confirmed that the negotiation which was being
made possible by the "positive statement" of the new U.S.
ambassador to Nigeria is expected to climax very shortly with the
resolution on areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi is scheduled to meet Ambassador William Twaddell in the
capital Abuja to find common grounds for strengthening bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of their meeting is the restoration of the
airlink between the two countries, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Washington severed direct airlink with Nigeria in August 1993
for alleged lack of safety measures in Nigeria aircraft and
airports.
</P>
<P>
In the same vein, the British Department of Transport banned
on May 15 last year all Nigeria-registered aircraft from flying
into its airspace over alleged non-compliance with safety
oversight by the Nigerian aviation authorities.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria retaliated the following day by banning all British
registered aircraft from its airspace.
</P>
<P>
Britain lifted the ban last August when British Airways
reportedly suffered huge losses, but the face-off remains as
Nigeria insists in a review of the bilateral air service
agreement for equal treatment.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, British Airways operates 14 flights a
week between the two countries, while Nigeria Airways does only
three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
