<HEADLINE> Israeli Official: No Troop Withdrawal From South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said today that there will be no Israeli troop
withdrawal from South Lebanon unless Israel's security is
guaranteed, Israel radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, who is on a tour of the security zone in South
Lebanon, also said that there will be no problem for Israel to
accept the U.N. Security Council resolution 425 calling for
Israel to withdraw from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But for the time being, he said, security is important
for Israel and Israel can not pull out its troops from the
security zone because the peace and security of the region has
not been ensured.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
South Lebanon in 1985 with an aim to protect its northern areas
from cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Mordechai told the London-based Arabic newspaper
Al-Watan Al-Arabi that Israel will accept the U.N. Security
Council resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, dating back to 1978, calls for an Israeli
withdrawal from South Lebanon, the restoration of peace and
security and the extension of Lebanese authority over the region.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the rest of his cabinet
expressed their support on Sunday for the statement made by
Mordechai that Israel will be willing to implement the
resolution, provided Israel reaches an agreement with the Lebanese
government to ensure security arrangements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
