<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Thelma Awori, assistant
administrator and director of the regional bureau for Africa in
the U.N. Development Program (UNDP), today pledged the
organization's support to development initiatives in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting on ''Dialogue with Development
Partners'' at the United Nations Conference Center here, the
visiting official said the UNDP would make efforts to help
African countries achieve their national development programs.
</P>
<P>
She referred to the UNDP's program for Africa on health and
nutrition, basic education, water and sanitation, food security,
gender and development as well as the U.N.'s systemwide special
initiative on Africa which was launched in May, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Awori also discussed with representatives of the United
Nations organizations, the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
donor agencies, non-governmental organizations and private
sectors on how to enhance the role of UNDP in Africa's
development activities.
</P>
<P>
Awori, a Ugandan, was appointed assistant administrator and
director of the regional bureau for Africa in the UNDP in
September last year. She is currently paying a visit to Ethiopia
from January 4 to 7, 1998. During her stay here, she met
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, OAU Secretary General
Salim Ahmed Salim and Executive Secretary of the U.N. Economic
Commission for Africa K.Y. Amoako. 
