<HEADLINE> S. Leone Accuses ECOMOG of Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone today reacted
strongly to the ECOMOG commander who said that 10,000 troops
currently in Liberia are to be deployed in Freetown "with or
without the consent" of the ruling military junta.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Commander of the west African Peace-keeping Force
(ECOMOG), General Victor Malu made the statement in Monrovia
Monday as he planned to return to Nigeria on the coming Thursday
to head a military training college.
</P>
<P>
"The statement disregards Sierra Leone's territorial
sovereignty and tantamounts to a declaration of war," charged
Amedu Bah, the junta public relations officer.
</P>
<P>
"It is an act of aggression which we as a government is
capable of resisting. ECOMOG has no such mandate of unilaterally
bringing in troops just like that. It proves how Nigeria is
taking unilateral decisions in the guise of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS)," he added.
</P>
<P>
The military junta frowns on ECOMOG as the later imposed
sanctions to force it to return power in April to the civilian
government it ousted last October in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as the current wave of fightings between government
soldiers and Kamajors rages on in the southeast, political
analysts said the Conakry Peace Agreement is "now almost in
tatters."
</P>
<P>
Travelers arriving in the capital early today from war-torn
areas in the south reported fresh fightings on the outskirts of
Bo, the second biggest city of the country.
</P>
<P>
In one of such attacks to dislodge the Kamajors from their
base, said an eyewitness, government soldiers overpowered the
militia who subsequently ran out of ammunition and fled into
different safety zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
