<HEADLINE> Cook: No Intention of Quitting Foreign Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook flatly denied here today wide-spread British media
speculation that he is to resign his post to run for the First
Minister in the new Scottish Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the House of Commons Foreign Affairs Committee this
afternoon, Cook said: "I am thoroughly enjoying this job and I
have no intention of giving it up."
</P>
<P>
Cook, holds a parliament seat for Edinburgh, Scotland, had been
reportedly interested in seeking the senior post in the Scottish
parliament due to be established in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Cook told the Committee that the new Scottish First Minister's
position will be "a very large and exciting job."
</P>
<P>
"But I am not in the market looking for a new job. I am staying
Foreign Secretary. I am not applying for any other job," Cook
added.
</P>
<P>
The new Scottish parliament will be vested with powers to vary
income tax by up to three percent from English levels and with
strong powers in areas such as education, health, the environment
and agriculture. 
</P>
