<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan to Join Efforts on Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Pakistan today announced
their readiness to make joint efforts to bring peace to the
war-torn Afghanistan, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The stance of the two neighbors of Afghanistan was announced
in a meeting between Pakistani special envoy on Afghanistan
issue Iftikhar Murshid and his Iranian counterpart Alaeddin
Boroujerdi this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Murshid said in the meeting that Pakistan would continue its
talks with Iran on the Afghan issue until its final solution,
adding that the Pakistani government has reached the conclusion
that dialogue among various Afghan groups was the only way for the
Afghan rival leaders to reach understanding among them.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Pakistan as two important neighbors of Afghanistan
should spare no efforts to bring peace in the war-torn central
Asian country, said the Pakistani official who arrived here this
morning for a two-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
Referring to recent talks between Pakistani officials and the
Afghan Taliban group, he said that Islamabad has encouraged the
Taliban to join the Afghan peace talks and it would continue this
policy in the future.
</P>
<P>
Iran's special envoy on the Afghan issue Boroujerdi also
voiced Tehran's willingness to cooperate with Islamabad over the
Afghan issue, but expressing concern over Taliban's refusal to a
ceasefire during the Islamic holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran, as chairman of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC), would continue its efforts to implement
the OIC resolutions on Afghanistan in order to restore peace in
that country.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the needs to dispatch more humanitarian
assistance to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
According to Pakistani ambassador to Iran Javid Hossain,
Murshid's visit was aimed at exchanging views with Iranian
officials and seeing "how the two countries can work together in
encouraging the peace talks in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has backed the Taliban forces while Iran supported
former Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani, whose government was
ousted by the Taliban forces in September, 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the OIC summit held here last month, Iran and Pakistan
jointly proposed a resolution on Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
