<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Team Ascends Africa's Highest Peak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhang Dacheng, Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- For the first time, a team of
Chinese mountaineers have successfully conquered the 5,895-meter high
peak of Uhuru in Mt. Kilimanjaro, the highest in Africa, sources said
this evening.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhixin and Wang Yongfeng from the Chinese Mountain-Climbing
Team reached the top of the peak at 07:40 local time (04:40 GMT) on
Monday, said Li, the team leader, from their base camp at the foot of
the mountain.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, Li said that starting at
02:00 in the morning, the team, braving severe snowstorm, chose a
difficult route and finally erected a Chinese national flag on the
peak.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the members of the Chinese
Mountain-Climbing Team to ascend the top of Kilimanjaro located in
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Three Chinese journalists, Wang Haozheng, female, from the Beijing
Youth Daily, and Zhang Wei and Pan Yansheng, from the China Central
Television, also climbed along with the two mountaineers to a camp as
high as 4,750 meters.
</P>
<P>
As professional and excellent mountaineers, Li Zhixin and Wang
Yongfeng have so far conquered the world's highest mount Qomolangma in
Asia as well as the highest mountains in North America, South America,
Europe and the Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
Their next goal is to climb up the highest mountain in Oceania,
thus completing their ambitious plan to conquer all the highest
mountains in the seven continents of the world.
</P>
<P>
The snow-capped Kilimanjaro, which is an active volcano located
near the Equator, attracts a great number of mountaineers as well as
tourists every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
