<HEADLINE> Nigeria Debunks S. Leone's Claims on Ethnic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian military today debunked
claims by Sierra Leone's ruling junta that officers of Yoruba
extraction involved in peacekeeping operations in S.Leone had
been arrested and sent back home for trial.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing here, Defense Spokesman Godwin Ugbo said
that no Nigerian military officer involved in any overseas operation had
been brought back home for trial.
</P>
<P>
The junta was just exploiting Internet services to perpetuate
falsehood, he said, adding that "There is no iota of truth in the
allegation."
</P>
<P>
Ugbo, who described the junta's claims as " mischievous and
malicious", noted that it was aimed at causing disharmony among
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The alleged claims followed the arrest of Nigeria's Chief of
General Staff, Oladip Diya, and 11 others in connection with
a foiled coup plot uncovered by the Nigerian government on December 21
last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of those arrested are from the Yoruba ethnic group, one of the
largest in Nigeria mainly living in the west.
</P>
<P>
Ugbo further described the claims as an attempt by the junta to
cover up the break-up in its ranks, citing the recent dismissal of
several of its leading members for looting the Iranian embassy in
Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The sacked members included Tamba Gborie, who announced the
military coup on May 25 last year, ousting President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
He was also reported to try to attack the residence of the junta
leader Johnny Paul Koroma.  
</P>
