<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Trade Deficit Slightly Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's balance of trade deficit
slightly decreased to 25,775 million Egyptian pounds (7,580.9
millon U.S. dollars) last year, representing a 0.73 percent drop
over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency quoted a report by the Ministry of
Trade and Supply as saying that the total imports in 1997 rose by
1.54 percent to 36,663.8 million pounds (10,783.5 million
dollars), the volume of exports increased by 7.34 percent to
10,888.32 million pounds (3,202.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that exports of non-petroleum products
increased to 6,255.75 million pounds (1,839.9 million dollars) in
1997, a 15.32 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
The volume of non-petroleum imports increased by 0.56 percent
to 36,265.5 million pounds (10,666.3 million dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Asian, African and South American countries
increased by 56.25 percent in 1997, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Raw cotton exports increased by 60 million pounds (17.6 million
dollars) in 1997 to reach 329.42 million pounds (96.9 million
dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
Semi-manufactured exports rose to 1,675.84 million pounds
(492.9 million dollars) in the past year, a growth of 242
million pounds (71.2 million dollars) over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
While exports of manufactured products rose by 652 million
pounds (191.8 million dollars), standing at 3,567.71 million
pounds (1,049.3 million dollars) in the past year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
