<HEADLINE> Iranian President Faces Pressure in Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami is facing mounting pressures as the countdown started for
his first address to the "great American people" scheduled on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers from the right-wing factions recently published
interviews and speeches of hardline political officials,
lawmakers and religious figures, voicing opposition to any
contacts or dialogues with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The time is not ripe for resumption of diplomatic ties with
the United States and the resumption will only cause Iran to lose
its dignity, political independence and the Islamic nature of the
country," local newspapers Tehran Times and Resalat quoted their
interviewees as saying.
</P>
<P>
On December 14, soon after the conclusion of the summit of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) in Tehran, Khatami
announced his readiness to have a dialogue with the "great
American people," a proposal welcomed by top U.S. officials
including President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Parliament member Mohammad Hussein Zare said that it would be
no use to develop contacts with the United States because "the
history of our contacts with the U.S. and our experience with that
nation have sufficiently proved that the U.S. does not pay any heed
to our interests or it would be more appropriate to say that they
do not care for others."
</P>
<P>
He said that any contacts, which can be fruitful or can
enhance the prestige of the Islamic Revolution, should be
welcomed, but "the case of the United States is different from
others."
</P>
<P>
"President Khatami in his address to the people of the
U.S. should explain the realities and clarify the
misunderstandings created by the U.S. government in a deliberate
attempt to distort the image of the Islamic Revolution," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Many Iranian officials criticized Washington for the
continuation of its hostile policies toward Iran, saying that "so
far the U.S. has not demonstrated any change in its attitude
toward Iran."
</P>
<P>
"When President Khatami decided to send a message to the
people of the United States, the U.S. officials put forward a
series of conditions" for a possible dialogue between the two
sworn enemies, said Mahmoud Alavi, another parliament member.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said earlier that
"the ball is in the American court."
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to work with all nations, provided they are
ready to establish relations with us based on mutual respect,"
Kharrazi said, adding that there would be no dialogue between
Tehran and Washington unless the U.S. changes its policies toward
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
