<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Differences Over Cairo Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The National Salvation Council
(NSC) of Somalia today announced here that differences among Somali
faction leaders over the recent Cairo Agreement have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, five co-chairmen of the NSC
said they convened the 3rd regular meeting here and agreed to take
measures to correct the Cairo Agreement.
</P>
<P>
They said the measures taken to correct the Cairo Agreement will
be discussed with Hussein Aideed.
</P>
<P>
They described the recent Cairo meeting as supplementary to
the peace and reconciliation process, and said although the Cairo
conference had included Hussein Aideed, the boycott by two
co-chairmen of the NSC widened the misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
The two co-chairmen walked out the Cairo negotiations saying the
power sharing in the future Somali government is not based on fair
representation, the co-chairmen said.
</P>
<P>
According to the co-chairmen, they reached an agreement after
making amendments on the question of fair representation based on
clan.
</P>
<P>
They said they have agreed to hold a reconciliation conference
in Baidoa beginning on February 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the evacuation of Hussein Aideed's militia from Baidoa
is made a precondition for the convening of the reconciliation
conference, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Baidoa conference will discuss the structure of the future
Somali government which they said will be headed by a prime
minister and have a 180 member General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The self-proclaimed Somaliland President, Mohammed Igal will
attend the conference as individual participant, according to the
co-chairmen. 
</P>
