<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Gets Boost in Nigeria's New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today announced to
provide 46.28 billion Naira (about 579 million U.S. Dollars) for
the infrastructure sector this year, the highest among all
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The amount represents 18.96 percent of the total sectoral
allocation in this year's budget, said Finance Minister Anthony
Ani in presenting a budget breakdown in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The sector is followed by education with 26.7 billion Naira
(about 334 million dollars) or 10.94 percent, and defense with
23.08 billion Naira (about 289 million dollars) or 9.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In last year's budget, the two sectors accounted for 7.68
percent and 7.42 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the breakdown, which was relayed on the
television network, 22 billion Naira (275 million dollars) or
9.02 percent is allocated to domestic debt servicing as against
12 billion Naira last year.
</P>
<P>
The allocation to industry, solid minerals, commerce and
tourism, and steel totals 19.22 billion naira (240 million
dollars), accounting for 7.87 percent of the budget, while that
to the police is 16.6 billion Naira (208 million dollars) or 6.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The share of health sector stands at 4.9 percent, or 11.93
billion naira (149 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the government budget, released by Head of State
General Sani Abacha Sunday night, the country's gross revenue is
estimated at 424 billion Naira (about 5.3 billion dollars) and
total expenditure at 329 billion Naira (4.1 billion dollars) this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
