<HEADLINE> Egypt Expects to Improve Relations with Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior advisor to Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak said today that Egypt expects the turning
of "a new leaf" in its relations with Sudan, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt welcomes turning a new leaf in Sudanese-Egyptian
relations in all domains," said Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's political
advisor, while addressing an Islamic forum co-sponsored by Egypt's
Ministry of Waqfs (Religious Endowments) and Al-Azher, the country's
highest Islamic institution.
</P>
<P>
In a show of rapprochement with Khartoum, whom Egypt has
accused of harboring militants who try to overthrow Egypt's secular
government, Baz described the Cairo-Khartoum ties as "time-honored
and highly special."
</P>
<P>
He also referred to the recent statements by some Sudanese
officials calling for iron out their differences in bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Amid signs of improved Cairo-Khartoum ties, Egyptian Trade and
Supply Minister Ahmed Gowaili has invited his Sudanese counterpart
Othman al-Hadi to visit Egypt in mid-January for talks on
enhancing joint investment and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, a delegation of the Sudanese Ministry of
Communications and Transports arrived here for talks on
resuming Nile navigation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On January 3, Sudanese First Vice President Zubeir Mohammed
Salih confirmed that Egyptian and Sudanese efforts for restoring
bilateral relations are going in full swing and will be crowned by
a visit of President Omar al-Bashir to Egypt soon.
</P>
<P>
The present thaw in bilateral relations followed assurances
from Khartoum that it will no longer provide support for Islamic
militants attempting to undermine the Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has already nominated its ambassador to Cairo and Egypt is
expected to nominate its ambassador to Khartoum soon.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Egypt and Sudan have been strained after Egypt
accused Sudan of supporting terrorism and plotting to assassinate
Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, in June 1995. Sudan has denied
the accusations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
