<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Turkey For Violation of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Greece today criticized Turkey for
violation of its airspace, saying that this did harm to the mutually
agreed stance of respecting major religious holidays.
</P>
<P>
When Greece celebrated Epiphany today, Turkish F-16s warplanes
infringed air control regulations in the Athens flight information
region (FIR) north and south of Lesvos island in the eastern
Aegean Sea and on 14 occasions violated Greek national airspace in
the region over the islands of Psara, Chios and Oenousses, the
Greek Defense Ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second time that the Turkish airforce is carrying out
provocations during a religious holiday in violation of an agreement
to refrain from such actions during religious holidays and
anniversaries, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the violations were not related to an ongoing
major Turkish wargame in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Greek Defense Undersecretary Dimitris Apostolakis
stressed that the Greek armed forces were cautiously monitoring the
Turkish military exercise and would take all necessary measures if the
manoeuvres were carried out in unauthorized Greek areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Greece and Turkey reached a "memorandum agreement" to
promote confidence-building measures between the two countries on the
principle of good-neighborliness. The agreement included respect of
each other's major religious holidays.
</P>
<P>
On Christmas Day, Athens also condemned Ankara for the violation of
its airspace by Turkish jet fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
