<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Reaffirms Stand on Advancing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu reaffirmed here today that only after
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) fulfills its commitment to
fight terrorism, the Mideast peace talks could be pushed forward.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis
Ross in the Prime Minister's Office, Netanyahu told reporters
that it is the duty of his coalition government, which just
survived the budget crisis Monday, to continue advancing the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This government was elected to advance the peace process
under the principles of the Palestinians' compliance with the
obligations given to us, given to the United States, and to the Oslo
Accord," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly stressed recently that the PNA must
adhere to all the commitments it undertook with regard to Israel's
security before the further redeployment in the West Bank can be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
The scope and timing of the second redeployment will also be
the main subject of the meeting between Netanyahu and Ross, who
arrived here today in a bid to narrow the differences between
Israel and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ross said that despite the political turmoil in Israel
generated by Foreign Minister David Levy's resignation over the
budget dispute, he would work with Netanyahu and PNA President
Yasser Arafat to advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his consultations with Israeli and Palestinian
officials will be a preparation for the expected meetings of
U.S. President Bill Clinton with Netanyahu and Arafat in
Washington later this month.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu confirmed Monday that the Israeli cabinet will draw
up a plan on the precise scope of the second pullback from the
West Bank before he leaves for Washington.
</P>
<P>
But analysts believed that it will be very difficult for
Netanyahu to finish a plan, which will satisfy both the
U.S. Administration and the members of his coalition, which was
dominated by extreme right-wingers after moderate Levy's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Netanyahu, Ross will go to the West Bank
city of Bethlehem tonight for talks with Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
