<HEADLINE> Egypt: Turkish-Israeli-US Maneuvers Ill Timed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today criticized the controversial naval exercises
involving troops of Turkey, Israel and the U.S. in the East
Mediterranean, saying the timing for the exercises is wrong.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that "Egypt does not see any
justification for carrying out these maneuvers at the present
time."
</P>
<P>
Egypt considers that the basis of the maneuvers, scheduled for
Wednesday, is wrong and the thinking and orientation on which they
are based are also wrong, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The timing of the maneuvers is wrong and consequently what is
built on this is also wrong, therefore this is considered a
negative step in the light of the stalled peace process and
intransigence in Israeli policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Military officials who will take part in the three-way drill
said the exercises are aimed at coordinating search-and-rescue
procedures and will not pose any threat to other countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Despite Arab criticism of the growing Israeli-Turkish military
cooperation, Jordan has decided to send an observer to the
controversial "Reliant Mermaid" exercises.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister, when asked on the impact of the
political crisis in Israel on the peace process, said the crisis
is Israel's internal affair.
</P>
<P>
"We shall wait to see what attitude the Israeli government will
adopt in the coming few days and the offers it will make at the
coming meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli
Prime Minister (Benjamin Netanyahu,)" Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Washington meeting is important as it is related to the
U.S. role and the Israeli attitude toward the peace process and
its future, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to meet separately with Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat in
Washington this month in order to end a nine-month-old crisis in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace-making.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock in the troubled Mideast peace process is coupled
with recent political turmoils in Israel over the resignation of
Foreign Minister David Levy, which has left Netanyahu's coalition
much weakened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
