<HEADLINE> Penalties on Gas Flaring Increase in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said today that penalties
on flaring natural gas have increased from 50 Kobo (half Naira)
per thousand cubic feet to 10 Naira (about 0.125 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new rate is part of measures the government has adopted to
end gas flaring in the country's oil fields and to promote gas
utilization, according to Finance Minister Anthony Ani in his
presentation of the 1998 budget breakdown in a nationwide
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The old rate was fixed in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, gas utilization projects will now
be taxed under the commercial companies tax act at 30 percent,
instead of being assessed under the petroleum tax regime at 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
Industries in the country are also encouraged to switch to the
use of gas in order to make the government goal realized.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's natural gas reserve is estimated at 150,000-300,000
billion cubic meters, ranking the 10th in the world.
</P>
<P>
But due to lack of utilization, most of the resources have
being flared, leading to serious environmental protection problem
and huge economic losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
