<HEADLINE> France Resumes Pursuit of Rwandan Priest Accused of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cour de Cassation, France's
highest court, Tuesday ordered the resumption of judicial pursuit
against Wenceslas Munyeshyaka, a Rwandan Roman Catholic priest
accused of joining the genocide against Tutsis in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Wenceslas was arrested and jailed in July 1995 by a French
court in Privas, Ardeche in southern France, for "genocide,
complicity in genocide, tortures, and inhuman and degrading
treatment."
</P>
<P>
But an appeal court in Nimes, southern France, ordered the
release of Wenceslas on March 20, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wenceslas served as the vicar of the Saint-Famille Church in
the Rwandan capital Kigali, where hundreds of Tutsi refugees took
refuge during the genocide from April to July 1994.
</P>
<P>
When the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front took Kigali,
Wenceslas fled Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Wenceslas is now serving as a Roman Catholic priest in Andelys
west of Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
