<HEADLINE> Jurors Continue to Deliberate Bombing Conspirator's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Jurors in Denver, Colorado,
resumed their deliberations Tuesday in an effort to determine
whether Terry Nichols should die for his lesser role in the
Oklahoma City bombing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The federal jury deliberated five hours Monday without reaching
a verdict.
</P>
<P>
The jurors convicted Nichols of conspiracy and involuntary
manslaughter on December 23 but acquitted him of first-degree
murder.
</P>
<P>
The basic inconsistency in the initial verdict is something
these jurors are having problems with now, according to news
reports.
</P>
<P>
Nichols was convicted of conspiracy and eight counts of
involuntary manslaughter for the April 19, 1995, bombing that
killed 168 people. In addition to first-degree murder, he also was
acquitted of use of a truck bomb in the deadliest terrorist act
ever on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
In June, co-conspirator Timothy McVeigh was convicted on eight
counts of first-degree murder and three other charges and
sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
Jurors must decide if Nichols should receive the same sentence,
life in prison or a lesser term to be determined by the judge. The
judge will sentence him on the involuntary manslaughter
convictions later.
</P>
<P>
Nichols was accused of helping McVeigh acquire key bomb
ingredients and hiding them. He was at home in Herington, Kansas,
when McVeigh set off the bomb.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
