<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Borrows No Foreign Loans Since 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Government has not
negotiated any new loans from international creditors since 1995,
Finance Minister Anthony Ani said today in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998 budget breakdown relayed on a nationwide broadcast, Ani
said that rather than enter into new credit agreements, the federal
government had started discussions with its creditors on the need to
get some debt reliefs and concessions.
</P>
<P>
He said that conscious efforts have been made to reconcile the
nation's debt figures with the creditors, including the London and
Paris Clubs.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Nigeria's aggregate foreign debt stock stood
at 27.08 billion U.S. Dollars as of December 31, 1997, compared with
28.06 billion dollars in 1996 and 32.58 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government had allocated two billion dollars
in this year's budget to service foreign debts, the same amount as
last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the successes recorded in the country's debt management in
the past two years, Ani said, the debt overhang would remain a heavy
burden without concessional debt relief from the foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
He said that following a successful negotiation of a medium-term
economic strategy with the World Bank and International Monetary Fund,
Nigeria would press for concessional debt relief from the creditors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
