<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Teachers Defy Junta's Call to Re-open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Teachers in Sierra Leone's capital
Freetown have defied a call by the Education Ministry to re-open
schools closed since the May 25 coup last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here said today, some children
waited at schools in the city for several hours Monday, hoping
their teachers would turn up, but the staff followed a boycott call by
the Sierra Leone Teachers' Union.
</P>
<P>
However, teaching resumed in some other parts of the west African
country, such as the major eastern town of Kenama and Makeni in the
north.
</P>
<P>
Education Ministry officials said Monday that they were deeply
disappointed by the failure of teachers to start a new term and
accused them and parents of gambling with their children's future.
</P>
<P>
The Teachers' Union said early last December tht teachers would
return to school this month if their demands were met, including a
claim for pay arrears and the junta's implementation of a peace plan
that will lead to the restoration of ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah by April.
</P>
<P>
"The re-opening of schools will happen if all armed personnel are
disarmed according to the Conakry peace plan and if those armed
fighters now occupying school premises are evacuated immediately," the
union said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, universities remained closed as many
academic staff fled abroad after the coup.  
</P>
</TEXT>
