<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Trilateral Exercise in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Tuesday defended its involvement in a trilateral exercises with
Israel and Turkey in the eastern Mediterranean, saying it was
only a "humanitarian operation."
</P>
<P>
"This exercise is a humanitarian exercise. It's about a
scenario in which a ship is suffering and needs assistance in a
humanitarian operation," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told reporters. "We think it's certainly appropriate for the
United States, Israel, and Turkey to engage in that."
</P>
<P>
But countries in the Middle East regarded the exercise, named
"Reliant Mermaid," as a threat to the region's security as the
exercise indicates a growing military ties between Israel and
Turkey and these countries were irked by U.S. involvement in the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Syria, in comment on the exercise, said on Saturday that the
maneuvers constituted "an encouragement to Israel to continue
its aggressions against peace and Arab and Islamic states."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Foreign Minister Amr Mussa on Sunday pointed out that
"Turkey must know that any alliance will trigger the establishment
of a counteralliance."
</P>
<P>
In response to Egypt's warning, Rubin repeated U.S.
supporting stance for the exercise, and said "we certainly don't
think it would justify any ramping up of any body else's
military considerations."
</P>
<P>
U.S. and Turkish vessels on Monday arrived at Israel's port
city of Haifa and three countries are now preparing for the
three-way exercise in the coming days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
