<HEADLINE> Germans Save Less Money, Says Bank Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Germans have cut their savings due
to low interest rates and joblessness, while investing more in
stocks, said a "Bank News" report released Wednesday in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
Germans put 5.2 billion marks (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) in
banks in the first nine months of 1997, compared to 52 billion
marks (29 billion dollars) in the same period of 1996, it said.
</P>
<P>
The decrease of deposits was because of the country's current
low interest rate of 3 percent on savings, rising unemployment as
well as the shift of money to stocks, said the report. 
