<HEADLINE> Party Leader Suggests Extending Tribunal to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- the president of the centrist
Union for French Democracy, Francois Leotard, Wednesday suggested
extending the International Tribunal on war crimes in the former
Yugoslavia and Rwanda to Algeria.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that France, and perhaps with the support of Britain,
the chairman of the European Union, could take the initiative of
an intervention by the (U.N.) Security Council ... to open the
field of application of the tribunals to the situation in
Algeria," Leotard said.
</P>
<P>
"No country can exercise its internal sovereignty while crimes
against humanity and war crimes are at work as those are today in
Algeria," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council created two international tribunals
to try suspected war criminals in the former Yugoslavia and
Rwanda. The two courts are based in the Hague, the Netherlands,
and Arusha, Tanzania. 
</P>
