<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Financial Policies Remain Appropriate: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong SAR secretary for
financial services, Rafael Hui, said here Wednesday that Hong
Kong's financial system has been proved to be sound and robust
during the financial crisis and existing relevant policies remain
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
"We do not consider an independent investigation committee
necessary," he said in a written reply to a question at a plenary
session of the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) about whether
 the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) would consider setting up such a committee to look into
matters relating to the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the financial crisis review being carried out by
the government, Hui noted that the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
has so far held five meetings with academics, analysts, bank
treasurers and capital market participants, apart from the
financial secretary's meeting with academics on November 14 last
year.
</P>
<P>
The discussions focused on the technical aspects of the
operation of the linked exchange rate system between the local
currency and the U.S. dollar and proposals made by the academics,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hui noted that there was clear support for the maintenance of
the pegged exchange rate system and general recognition that
volatility in interest rates cannot be avoided in the event of a
speculative attack or an external shock.
</P>
<P>
Hui went on to say that there has been good progress in the
financial review which is being carried out under three principles.
</P>
<P>
"First, the linked exchange rate system remains
unchanged. Secondly, Hong Kong's position as an international
financial center must be maintained. And thirdly, we should
address the operation of the financial markets and explore ways
to improve the technical aspects of the mechanism."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that some preliminary findings of the
review will be available next month.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's plenary session of the Provisional Legislative
Council, other SAR government officials also answered questions
concerning the measures to stem the source of bird flu, Hong
Kong's holidays and travel advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Legislators had the first and second reading of the Housing
(Amendment) (No.3) Bill 1997 at the session and a number of
motions tabled by government officials or PLC members were
adopted, including a motion to appoint Lord Nicholls of Birkenhead
and Lord Hoffman as judges of the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
