<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- France's extreme-right National
Front (FN) Wednesday presented 23 candidates for the regional
elections in March, among whom the FN leader Jean-Marie Le Pen
will run for presidency of the regional parliament in the southern
Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur region.
</P>
<P>
The number two of FN Bruno Megret said that the regional
elections would start at "a relatively critical moment of the
political situation" in France.
</P>
<P>
He said that the FN would focus his platform on three points:
unemployment, immigration and crimes.
</P>
<P>
The FN is trying to grasp some of the electorate among the
jobless people and the working class from the leftwing parties,
while playing up the problem of immigration which links with
crimes in cities and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
"We are at the beginning of a phenomenon of Intifadha of the
suburbs," he said in reference to the recent riots which took
place in poor suburbs where usually live a large number of Arab
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Le Pen, 69, will tour 10 cities during the regional election
campaign. 
