<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province of China Alleviates Abject Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The food problems for the
remaining 600,000 farmers living in abject poverty in south
China's Guangdong Province have basically solved.
</P>
<P>
Last year, these farmers had an increase of 300 yuan in
per-capita income, according to Cui Jian, director of the
province's Poverty Relief Office.
</P>
<P>
Officials in 33 counties pledged to resign from their posts if
they failed to succeed in extricating poverty-stricken farmers
from difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Some 103,000 officials were assigned to help 120,000 rural
households achieve an improved standard of living, with 21 million
yuan donated for relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels raised 240 million yuan, or an
average of 2,000 yuan per family in the province, to provide
funding for 220,000 relief projects.
</P>
<P>
The province reduced its poverty-stricken population from
four million in the past to 600,000 at the end of 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
