<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lost Ancient Chinese Paintings Housed Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 23,000 ancient Chinese
paintings are housed in collections overseas, including one of the
most famous Chinese paintings dating back some 1,600 years old.
</P>
<P>
The painting in question -- "Nu Shi Zhen" which depicts a
beautiful lady, was painted by Gu Kaizhi, a noted painting master
of the Eastern Jin Dynasty (317-420) who is considered to be the
father of traditional Chinese painting. The painting, looted by
the Allied Forces in 1860, is currently housed in London's Museum
of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
Other invaluable artifacts include painted pottery dating back
to the late Stone Age and bronze and jade pieces from the Xia
(21th-16th Century B.C.), Shang (16-11th Century B.C.) and Zhou
(11th Century-221 B.C.) dynasties, as well as silk painting pieces
from the Chu State of the Warring State Period (475-211 B.C.) and
numerous famous paintings from later dynasties.
</P>
<P>
"All of the works are of high academic and artistic value,"
according to Lin Shuzhong, a professor of art history at the
Nanjing Institute of Art in the capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
"The works constitute only a small part of Chinese works which
were taken overseas in the century following the Opium War in
1840," said Lin, adding that an untold number of works have not as
yet surfaced.
</P>
<P>
Lin noted that approximately 33 percent of the 23,000 paintings
are in the Americas, mainly in the United States and Canada, with
another 33 percent in Japan, and the remainder in European
nations, including Germany, Britain, France, Belgium and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of works in Europe were looted from a cave at
Dunhuang's Mogao Grottos in northwest China's Gansu Province at
the beginning of the century, with other works spirited overseas
between 1930-1940 when the country was in the midst of war and
neglected the protection of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who initiated his research of Chinese paintings in
overseas museums in 1985, is currently compiling an 800,000-word
pictorial of the 23,000 paintings.
</P>
<P>
The Hunan Fine Arts Publishing House will publish the book at a
cost of four million yuan (480,000 US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
