<HEADLINE> Malawian Kwacha Depreciates Drastically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian Kwacha has
depreciated drastically due to the government's fiscal
indiscipline, Zambia News Agency ZANA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Kwacha has depreciated from 15.35 to the U.S dollar in
July 1997 to 21.9 during the first week of January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted analysts as saying that unless the Malawian
government put brakes on its expenditure, the currency would
continue to fall.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to mitigate the negative effects is for Malawi
to reinforce fiscal discipline," said Matthew Chicaonda, governor
of the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
An International Monetary Fund (IMF) team, which was recently
in Malawi, said they were unhappy with what they found during
their routine review visit of the Malawi economy.
</P>
<P>
Although foreign aid has not been suspended, the economists
said, the government appeared to have contravened the agreements
with the fund to restrict its spending.
</P>
<P>
This may partly explain the sudden shortage of foreign
exchange on the Malawi market, they added, and hence the rapid
depreciation of the Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Kwacha is expected to continue until
April when the tobacco marketing season starts and dollars start
to flow into the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
