<HEADLINE> World Cup 2002 Rule Out Midnight Kickoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Kick-off times during the 2002
World Cup co-hosted by Japan and South Korea would not start at
midnight to satisfy European audiences, Asian soccer officials
said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is absurd to even think of such things (midnight
kick-offs). The World Cup is never focussed or timed for any
particular continent," said Peter Velappan, general secretary of
the Asian Football Confederation at Football Expo '98, FIFA's
first international soccer industry exhibition in Singapore this
week.
</P>
<P>
Velappan said a decision on kick-off times would be made after
this year's World Cup in France, but added that television would
"have a very big input" on it.
</P>
<P>
Tadao Murata, director of the Football Association of Japan,
co-organisers of the 2002 World Cup, said the final decision on
kick-off times depended on FIFA, the games world governing body,
and the TV company.
</P>
<P>
"They want to televise at the most valuable time. But no
decisions have been made yet," said Murata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
