<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Bankruptcies Hit Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Personal bankruptcies in the
United States hit record in 1997 despite an economic boom with low
unemployment and strong consumer confidence, Visa USA said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Visa USA, the world's largest credit card company, said 1.34
million credit card holders in America filed for bankruptcy in
1997, rising 19.5 percent from the 1.12 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Personal bankruptcies have increased by over 400 percent in the
country since 1980, the company said, based on findings by a daily
tracking system of all bankruptcies filed in federal courts.
</P>
<P>
While no states had a decline in the number of bankruptcies in
1997, West Virginia had the largest growth with a 54.2 percent
rise and Wyoming had the smallest with a 6 percent rise, it said.
</P>
<P>
One reason behind the record, it said, is the fact that there
was less stigma attached to bankruptcy, with many people now
willing to pursue it as a first opinion instead of a last resort.
</P>
<P>
"Many of these people could have avoided bankruptcy altogether
had they been aware of options like credit counseling, said Visa
USA's Senior Vice President Kenneth Crone.
</P>
<P>
He said Congress is considering new laws which would require
courts to inform debtors of alternatives to bankruptcy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
