<HEADLINE> Paris to Collect Less Tax From Parisians in 1998: Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Paris Mayor Jean Tiberi said
Wednesday his municipal government will collect less tax from
residents of the city in 1998 compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
In a New Year good wish message sent to deputies of the Council
of Paris, the local parliament, Tiberi said "fiscal pressure" on
residents of this capital city will diminish in this year.
</P>
<P>
The tax reduction measure, likely to be announced next week
before it is submitted to the city council for approval, followed
tax increases of 4.5 percent in 1997 and 6.9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
City officials said the reduction will be "considerable," so as
to achieve zero growth of tax collection on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Both the municipal government and city council of Paris are
controlled by the Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR).
</P>
<P>
The tax reduction could be a move to win support for the RPR in
the forthcoming regional elections scheduled for March, as the RPR
is expected to be challenged by the Socialist Party in Paris.
</P>
