<HEADLINE> China's Largest Saltwater Lake Well Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Province in northwest
China has been making progress in protecting the Qinghai Lake, the
largest saltwater lake in China.
</P>
<P>
The lake abounds in huso sturgeons, a rare species of fish.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 the province initiated a ban on fishing on the lake,
which covers 4,400 square kilometers and is known for the unique
sight of fish and birds peacefully coexisting. The ban's aim was
to recover the diminishing huso sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
The fish gains only half a kilogram in weight on average in
a decade due to adverse conditions, experts said.
</P>
<P>
They further warned that the birds would fly away if the fish
were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Local fishing administration departments have stopped many lake
poachers, and more than 2,000 have been punished.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission and the Ministry of Agriculture
have decided to spend 4 million yuan to help restore the fish
population, local sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
