<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Survived With Tough Win in Hopman Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia's world number two
Pat Rafter stormed his way back from the brink of defeat to beat
Spain's Carlos Moya and keep alive the host nation's hopes in the
Hopman Cup in Perth on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, the U.S. Open champion, trailed 1-4 in the third set
after losing formidably the second 1-6 to Spain's world number
seven Carlos Moya.
</P>
<P>
But he managed to capture his belated rhythm and rallied from
the brink of defeat against the Barcelona baseliner to win 7-5,
1-6, 7-6 (8-6).
</P>
<P>
"It was a very tough match. I am annoyed with myself for having
let him back in," the 25-year-old Queenslander said.
</P>
<P>
Rafter's win brought a crucial tie at 1-1 against top seeds
Spain and kept Australia's hopes alive in the mixed teams event
when Spaniard Arantxa Sanchez Vicario defeated Rafter's teammate
in their earlier clash.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez had an easier passage, winning the home country's
inexperienced Annabel Ellwood in straight sets 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
In the deciding mixed doubles the Australian team beat the
Spanish duo 7-5, 6-2 for a 2-1 win over the top seeds in the
eight-team round robin tournament.
</P>
<P>
Rafter and Ellwood on Thursday meet Karol Kucera and Karina
Habsudova of the Slovak Republic for a place in Saturday's final.
</P>
</TEXT>
