<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End 1.5 Pct Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
lost nearly 1.5 percent Wednesday as profit takers capitalized on
recent gains in banking stocks while resources were sold off on a
poor commodities outlook.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 38.4 points to 2,646.9. "Stocks
with exposure overseas, earning other currencies, were quite
strong and stocks with Australian exposure were a bit weak," Steve
Negrine from Reynolds and Co said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 53.2 points to 4,563.2, with the
fall led by banking stocks which had experienced strong recent
rises on the flight into high yielding shares in the wake of
falling bond yields.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank dropped 58 cents while Westpac was 13
cents lower, and there was also profit taking in ANZ, which fell
eight cents while Commonwealth Bank held up against the market to
lose four tenths of a cent.
</P>
<P>
News Corp shares, which had benefited on the low dollar and
receipts from its Fox studio's successful Titanic movie, also fell
17 cents.
</P>
<P>
Telstra's installment receipts were also sold off, down seven
cents.
</P>
<P>
The day's sharpest falls came in resources, with the major
stocks sold down significantly on a cautionary mode caused by a
doubtful outlook for any improvement in commodities stocks.
</P>
<P>
WMC was hit the hardest, dropping 32 cents while MIM was also
sold off by the market, down four cents, BHP also suffered,
falling 36.7 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 28.4 points to 1,114.5.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 19.9 points lower at 982.4. Gold stocks
were also sold off despite a 0.55 US dollar per ounce rise in the
bullion price to 281.45 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was a tepid 271.22 million shares
at a value of 675.27 million Australian dollars (432.17 million US
dollars), with falls outnumbering rises 677 to 388.  
</P>
