<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Short-Term Debts Only 30% of Total Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's short-term debts
as of the end of June in 1997 accounted for only 30 percent of the
total external outstanding debts, the State Bank announced here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This contrasted significantly to the ratio of 56 percent
published earlier by the Zurich-based Bank of International
Settlement (BIS), the State Bank, the country's central bank, said
in a statement issued here.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the BIS data refers only to bank lending,
a higher proportion of which is short-term.
</P>
<P>
"Including medium and long-term debts with remaining maturity
of one year, the ratio would be 39 percent," the State Bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that as of the end of June, 1997, Malaysia's total
borrowing, comprising short-, medium- and long-term debts,
amounted to 45.2 billion U.S. dollars, or 42 percent of its gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
These loans include inter-company borrowing, bonds raised in
the international capital markets and bank lending.
</P>
<P>
Medium- and long-term debts accounted for 70 percent or 31.7
billion dollars of the total external debts, the bulk of which
(63 percent) are with remaining maturity of between four and 20
years, the State Bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
