<HEADLINE> Singapore Ready to Stop Attacks on Its Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS), the de facto central bank of Singapore, said on
Wednesday that it is ready to stop any speculative attacks on the
Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore currency fell further to 1.78 against the U.S.
dollar at one point of the day's trading, hitting the lowest level
in six years. Other regional currencies continued to decline to
their new record lows on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The MAS emphasized in a statement that it manages the currency
against a trade-weighted basket of currencies "and not against any
single currency."
</P>
<P>
While the Singapore dollar has weakened against the U.S.
dollar, the Deutsche mark and pound sterling, the MAS said, it has
risen against the Malaysian ringgit, the Thai baht and the
Indonesian rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, on a trade-weighted basis, its (the Singapore
dollar's) value has remained stable, notwithstanding the currency
turmoil," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar has depreciated by about 18 percent since
July last year when the currency stood at 1.43 to the greenback.
</P>
</TEXT>
