<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police Get New System for Better Emergency Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- With the introduction of the
Caller Number Display (CND) system here on Wednesday, Hong Kong
police can now achieve greater efficiency in the 999 emergency
service, according to senior Police officers.
</P>
<P>
The CND system has been provided for all 999 operators at Hong
Kong Police's Regional Command and Control Center of Hong Kong
Island (RCCC/HKI) since early December last year.
</P>
<P>
With the new system, all incoming telephone numbers can now be
seen at 999 operators telset at the center, Chiu Yat-sing, chief
telecommunications engineer, told a RCC/HKI press conference on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nuisance calls which range from children playing with the
telephone to people maliciously making hoax calls always tie up
999 lines, reducing the efficiency of the 999 service and making
callers in genuine emergency difficult to gain access, he said.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are under way to install the CND system at RCCCs
in Kowloon and the "New Territories" and it is expected that the
two RCCCs will have the system by April this year after the
telephone system is upgraded there.
</P>
<P>
"The system is very useful to deal with hoax or nuisance
telephone callers," said Peter Hunt, senior superintendent of
support at the Hong Kong Police Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
With the new system, the 999 operators now can find the
locations of the callers through telephone companies. This can be
achieved even if the callers cannot give their locations because
either they are too confused, or they don't know where they are or
they just don't have time, Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
And the 999 operators can still register the telephone numbers
in case of line blocking or call blocking as they are provided
with a blocking override device on all calls to 999, he said.
</P>
<P>
The number of nuisance calls is likely to drop when all callers
 to 999 are aware that their telephone numbers will be displayed
on the 999 operators telset and that tracing of such calls has
now become easier. And action could be taken against persistent
nuisance callers, Hunt added.
</P>
<P>
When replying questions about the language used by the 999
operators, Hunt said all the telecommunications officers speak
English and Cantonese and two-thirds of them can speak Putonghua.
</P>
<P>
However, efforts are being made to encourage all the officers
to be "tri-lingual and bi-literate," including arranging courses
for the officers and giving them appropriate training, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
