<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Price Slumps To 18-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) - The price of gold fell to its
lowest since 1970s with the London market fixing the morning price
on Tuesday at 281.80 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Although the price recovered one dollar in the afternoon
price-fixing session, it still fell 1.60 dollars an ounce on the
day.
</P>
<P>
Gold was last at that level on July 3, 1979 - though it soared
to end that year at 524 dollars an ounce and reached 850 dollars
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
There has been a steady slide in the price during the 1980s and
1990s as bullion lost its investment appeal.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the latest fall came as investment funds
short-sold gold again and Australian mining companies have moved
to hedge future production.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was also damaged by the national campaign in
South Korea to persuade citizens to sell personal gold jewelry
for dollars.
</P>
<P>
The campaign began on Monday and a further 6.8 tons were handed
in on Tuesday, bringing the total to ten tons, valued at about 100
million dollars on world markets.
</P>
<P>
The gold price has also been under pressure after comments by
Alan Greenspan, Chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, that with
inflation under control, deflation could prove to be a problem for
the U.S. economy in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have been worried by signs that central banks, which
hold reserves sufficient to meet worldwide demand for the next ten
years, are considering disposing of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Central Bank last year admitted selling two
thirds of its stocks - the first time a leading gold producer had
disposed of its reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Central Bank -- one of the largest institutional gold
holders -- has also hinted that it may sell 1400 tons.
</P>
<P>
The market is likely to remain nervous before publication of
the Gold Fields Mineral Services report on Thursday, which will
provide estimates of supply and demand last year and could reveal
if any central banks have made further disposals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
