<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Thai Baht's Fall Still Unpredictable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The grim moment has eventually
come when the Thai currency has devalued by more than 100 percent
in exchange with the U.S. dollar since its float last year and it
is expected to continue its fall although the extent of the
decline is hard to predict.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the second trading day in the new year, the
exchange rate sank 2.3 baht to close at a historical low of 52.2
baht to the dollar, after dipping to as low as 52.75 in local
trade.
</P>
<P>
Offshore, the baht fared even worse, dropping to as low as
54.75 per dollar before picking up to close at 52.50/53.00.
</P>
<P>
The baht's nose-dive on Wednesday followed the slide on Monday
when the currency closed at 49.9 onshore and 50.10/50.40 offshore
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Before it was floated on July 2, the Thai currency's exchange
rate had been pegged, for 13 years, to a basket of foreign
currencies, with the U.S. dollar weighing about 80 percent. In
most of the 13 years, the baht moved within a very small range of
between 25.50 and 26.50 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Compared with its pre-float value of 25.79 to the dollar, the
baht has plunged by 100 percent against the dollar when the
exchange rate hits 51.58 baht. This means that a baht holder will
have to pay exactly twice as much to buy one U.S. dollar and his
assets in dollar terms are worth half as much as before the float.
</P>
<P>
The free fall of the baht in recent weeks has been primarily
driven by an investor confidence crisis, locally and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Before New Year's Day, Prime Minster Chuan Leekpai said that
the Thai economy would not start bottoming out until the third
quarter, instead of the earlier-predicted second quarter, of 1998
and that because of the impact of the regional money markets, the
baht will experience further turbulence before it stabilizes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, although Thailand has enjoyed a surplus in foreign
trade in recent months, demand for dollars still outstrips supply
in the domestic market as local corporations buy forward cover to
hedge against future foreign debt repayments.
</P>
<P>
Another critical factor pushing the baht downward is the
capital flight of about 3 billion U.S. dollars per month. The
withdrawal of about 100 million dollars per day by foreign
investors from the country creates added demand for the greenback
in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
A treasury dealer said that at 50-52 baht to the dollar, there
are not going to be many players willing to speculate short term
in the market. The demand for dollars is very real and comes from
local firms needing to repay their foreign debt and foreign
investors pulling out of their baht-denominated assets.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of Suthee Losoponkul, vice president of
Nakornthon Bank, there are three main factors driving down
confidence in the baht: the country's relatively high level of
foreign debt, which exceeds its gross domestic product; the fact
that a large proportion of foreign debt is short-term; and that
most foreign borrowing had not been hedged for currency risk
before the baht was floated.
</P>
<P>
Even the International Monetary Fund (IMF) had misjudged the
real strength of the baht as it did not expect that the currency
could have plummeted to such a low in six months after its float.
</P>
<P>
When the IMF signed its 17.2 billion dollar bailout package
with Thailand in early August last year, the program was based on
an estimate of about 33 baht to the dollar, much higher than the
present exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the IMF at that time believed incorrectly, and acted
accordingly, that Thailand's monetary crisis was only an isolated
case and that it would not be adversely affected by other
currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Now the question is that if the IMF, which is supposed to have
the world's top-most economic wizards, made misjudgments and
miscalculations, who on earth at this stage can predict how much
lower the baht will sink?
</P>
<P>
But one thing seems certain: With so many adverse domestic and
regional factors and the IMF's suspected wrong medicine, the
baht's decline will continue for some time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Official Complains about Arrest of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETWON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Abu Sillah, president of the
professional Drivers Association, said today that he is currently
negotiating with Nigerian troops in ECOMOG in Sierra Leone for
the release of over 15 drivers arrested and detained at the Jui
checkpoint since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The checkpoint is 13 miles east of the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
According to Sillah, five trucks from Kono and Konoma in the
east, and Bo in the south conveying produce and other essential
foodstuffs to Freetown were intercepted by the troops.
</P>
<P>
He said another vehicle belonging to the state-run National
Petroleum Company with 1,800 gallons of diesel for Nakoni in the
north as well as nine trucks going to neighbouring Guinea were
also intercepted.
</P>
<P>
Sillah said passengers on board the vehicles were allowed to
remove perishable goods such as cassava, potatoes and oranges
from the vehicles on Sunday but were not allowed to take away
cash crops such as cocoa and coffee.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some of the drivers were airlifted without
explanation to another ECOMOG base manned by Nigerian soldiers at
the Lungi International Airport, some 10 miles across the Sierra
Leone estuary.
</P>
<P>
Sillah said when his office was contacted about the incident,
he visited the ECOMOG base at Jui but was referred to ECOMOG
Military Intelligence Unit at Kossoh Town, two miles from Jui.
</P>
<P>
"The officers said they had received orders from the ECOMOG
High Command in Liberia to intercept commercial vehicles," Sillah
added.
</P>
<P>
He quoted the officers as saying, "our action is part of the
economic sanction on Sierra Leone which we are now enforcing."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the military junta has protested to
ECOWAS headquarters in Nigeria over what it called "the inhuman
treatment" of two Lieutenants in the Sierra Leone People's Army
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Defense sources said the two military officers in separate
incidents were punched, kicked and stripped bare by Nigerian
soldiers when they found a pistol and some light arms on board
their vehicles. The junta described the action by the Nigerian
soldiers as barbaric and the culprits should be disciplined.
</P>
</TEXT>
