<HEADLINE> Perth Opens Its Second Swimming Worlds in Eight Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The 8th world swimming
championships opened here on Wednesday night with a record
participation of more than 2,400 competitors and officials from
125 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
It was the second swimming Worlds for Perth, a western
Australian port which jumped out of oblivion in the sports world
by holding the 1991 championships.
</P>
<P>
The championships features swimming, diving, synchronized
swimming and water polo, and will end on January 18.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony saw the world's all-time aqautic greats
come together -- the United States' Mark Spitz and Greg Louganis,
Hungary's Krisztina Egerszegi, Russia's Vladimir Salnikov and
Australia's Murray Rose and Shane Gould.
</P>
<P>
Between them, there are 29 Olympic gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States split the men's and women's
5-kilometer open water swimming titles in the morning, the only
two events held prior to the opening ceremony. 
</P>
