<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Jet Drops Bombs in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian jet belonging to
the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG dropped at
least three cluster bombs on the Sierra Leonean capital Freetown
at 08:00 hours local time, sending market women into flight and
school children dashing to their homes.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately known why the bombs were dropped or the
extent of damage caused including loss of lives.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua correspondent heard the bombing sound in the west
of the city and unconfirmed reports suggested that the jet may
have threatened scores of merchants now milling near the Sierra
Leonean territorial waters in a bid to break the sanctions and
embargo imposed on the country in July by west African leaders.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the jet had dropped bombs in the city
after the signing of the Conakry agreement last October.
</P>
<P>
Bombings by Alfa jet planes killed over 100 people in assorted
raids on strategic targets in Freetown in September and October
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
