<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Ringgit Recovers After Bank Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's currency ringgit
recovered from an intra-day low to settle at 4.5900 to the U.S.
dollar Wednesday after intervention by the State Bank.
</P>
<P>
The local currency touched its lowest intra-day level of 4.8800
earlier in the day. But the day's closing level was still lower
when compared to Tuesday's close of 4.3450/50 as the demand for
the U.S. dollar remained strong.
</P>
<P>
The central bank was seen intervening in the foreign exchange
market to sell U.S. dollars at a range of 4.600 to 4.800 earlier
in the day, pushing the ringgit sharply up to 4.5900, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
"There are no fundamental reasons for the dollar/ringgit to go
up that high. The ringgit is just tracking the regional currencies
such as the Indonesian rupiah and the Thai baht which had fallen
quite badly," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The current regional financial crisis continued to put pressure
on the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
During the last few days, the ringgit was on a continuous
downward trend. On Monday, the ringgit breached the level of four
ringgit against the greenback due to prolonged commercial interest
for the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The local unit ended Monday at 4.0550/50 to the dollar from
last Friday's close of 3.9250./50.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim said in a statement issued earlier in the day that the
ringgit had now become grossly undervalued in an environment of
highly unstable market conditions.
</P>
<P>
He said "intervention operations" had been conducted to ensure
the efficient functioning of the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
"While Malaysia will continue to pursue a policy of flexible
exchange rates, these rates should reflect the underlying
fundamentals. It should not be a situation in which the exchange
rate determines the fundamentals," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for an open economy such as Malaysia, these
developments, if allowed to persist over a prolonged period, will
be damaging to the economic and financial fundamentals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
