<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second U.S. Noted Figure Killed in Skiing in a Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House Representative
Sonny Bono, an avid skier, died when he skied into a tree Monday
at a resort on the Nevada-California line, reports reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old Bono had been reported missing two hours before
his body was found at 6:45 p.m. Monday near South Lake Tahoe on
the California-Nevada border, about 90 kilometers south of Reno,
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
He was killed when he hit a tree, resort officials was quoted
as saying. Bono, who had skied at the resort for more than 20
years, was killed when he was skiing with his family.
</P>
<P>
A Bono spokesman, Frank Cullen Jr., said he was at the resort
in a family vacation. "He was a very proficient skier. He skied
frequently with his family and, yes, he was an athletic guy,"
Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
Bono had skied on ahead of other family members when the
accident happened.
</P>
<P>
His wife, Mary Whitaker, reported him missing about the time
the resort closed at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Bono's death came less than a week after Michael Kennedy,
39-year-old son of the late Robert F. Kennedy, was killed in a
skiing accident.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy was also killed when he smashed into a tree in playing
football on a ski slope in Aspen, Colorado, on the Eve of New Year.
</P>
<P>
Learning the news of Bono's death today, U.S. President Bill
Clinton said he was saddened.
</P>
<P>
"His joyful entertainment of millions earned him celebrity, but
in Washington he earned respect by being a witty and wise
participant in policymaking processes that often seem ponderous to
the American people," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich said he and his colleagues "lost a
very, very dear friend."
</P>
<P>
Flags were lowered to half staff over the Capitol in Washington
where Bono was serving his second term in the House.
</P>
<P>
He was elected mayor of Palm Springs in 1988 and was elected to
the House in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
