<HEADLINE> Optical Cable Lines Extending in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China laid 14 long-distance
optical cable lines in 1997, bringing the total length to 820,000
kilometers, according to sources of the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications here today.
</P>
<P>
Work on the 2,754-kilometer-long optical cable linking Lanzhou,
the capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, Xining, the
capital of northwestern Qinghai Province, and Lhasa, the capital
of the Tibet Autonomous region, has been completed. It runs
through 23 counties and cities in northwestern Gansu and Qinghai
provinces and Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A 970-kilometer-long land optical cable between Harbin, in
northernmost China's Heilongjiang Province, and Russia started
operation at the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
Construction of an optical cable linking China and the United
States, which will involve a total investment of 1.2 billion
U.S. dollars, began in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
China built 22 optical trunk lines in the period from 1991 to
1995 and expects to lay another 23 lines with a total length of
35,000 kilometers in the 1996-2000 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
