<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Toy Exports to Grow Ten Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, the world's biggest
exporter of toys, continued to hold its leading position in 1997
with a predicted ten percent growth.
</P>
<P>
In the first ten month of 1997, Hong Kong exported toys worth
77.76 billion HK dollars (ten billion U.S. dollars), an
encouraging rise of ten percent over the same period of 1996 given
the general market downturn in Asia, said Edmund Young, chairman
of the Trade Development Council's Toy Advisory Committee,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Hong Kong Toys and
Games Fair which opened here Wednesday, Young added that exports
of toys to the United States also went up by ten percent between
January and October last year. As the biggest export market for
Hong Kong toys, the United States took in 48.4 percent of the
Special Administrative Region's exports.
</P>
<P>
Other leading markets, including Japan, Western Europe, China's
inland areas and Canada, also registered substantial increases in
imports from Hong Kong, according to Young.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent financial turbulence in Asia, Young still
expected steadily growing demand from many key markets like the
United States and Western Europe in 1998. He said that South
America and the Middle East would be the fastest growing markets
in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong derives 70 percent of the industry sales from
licensing and contract manufacturing for overseas toy companies,
and the rest from making brand toys for overseas proprietary
product manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong toy companies have moved their factories to inland
provinces of China and other Asian countries to take advantage of
inexpensive labor and lower rents there. Currently, 95 percent of
Hong Kong's exports of toys are originated from the Chinese
inland areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
