<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecological Improvement Called Key to Relieving Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese economist said today
that ecological improvement might be a key to relieving poverty in
the mountainous areas of China where 84 percent of the country's
592 poor counties are located.
</P>
<P>
Most of the needy people who live in these areas suffer from
serious ecological destruction on northwest China's loess plateau,
or in southwest China's Yunnan, Guizhou and Sichuan provinces and
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous region, noted Shi Shan, vice-president
of the Ecological Economics Association of China.
</P>
<P>
The bad ecological factors in these areas include serious soil
erosion, the comparatively slow pace of replacing forests, the
rapid increase of sludge in rivers and lakes, and the degradation
of grasslands, Shi told a symposium on sustainable development in
poor rural areas which opened in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Ecologically friendly farming and integrated agricultural
development in river valleys have been feasible methods to improve
the ecology, he said.
</P>
<P>
China plans to provide enough food and clothing for 80 million
needy people during the 1994-2000 period. To date, only about 28
percent of the plan has been realized, with 58 million needy
people remaining to be fed, the symposium was told.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium is being sponsored by the China
Association for Science and Technology and the Amity Foundation, a
non-governmental organization which receives donations mainly from
overseas to aid China's needy people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
