<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Port Places 12th in World Container Shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- With last year's container
handling volume topping 2.5 million TEUs, the entry port of
Shanghai now ranks 12th in the world.
</P>
<P>
This largest port in China is marching toward the world's Top
Ten, said an official from the Hong Kong Oriental Overseas
Shipping Group, predicting that the port's handling capacity is
expected to reach 14 million TEUs (Twenty-foot Equivalent Units)
by 2007.
</P>
<P>
The port's sustainable annual growth rate, which has averaged
25 percent in recent years, has guaranteed its momentum. In 1995
the Shanghai port entered the world's Top 20 with its total volume
posting 1.53 million TEUs. A year later, it had 1.9 million TEUs,
ranking 17th in the world. Last year, its container shipping
volume increased 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's fast-growing economy and its role as China's largest
commercial and manufacturing center have been the major reasons
for the port's dramatic expansion, which now handles one quarter
of the country's international cargo shipping and a third of the
country's container shipping.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has nearly 20 shipping routes accommodating 281
dockings monthly to more than 50 countries and regions in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Shipping Trade Center was set up in November 1996
to standardize Shanghai's port transportation. It finished 36
million tons of cargo trade by the end of October 1997.
</P>
<P>
China plans to upgrade container ports in east China's Jiangsu
and Zhejiang provinces on the eastern coast to make them part of
an international container shipping hub. The construction will be
centered in Shanghai with an administrative institute set up here
last year.
</P>
<P>
Some projects have been launched, such as the rebuilding of
three container berths and massive dredge work in the deepwater
lane at the Yangtze River mouth.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the headquarters of the China Ocean Shipping Corp,
one of the four largest shipping groups in the world, will be
moved to the municipality this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
