<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes at New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The besieged Australian dollar
continued to falter Wednesday, hitting a new 11-year low of 63.19
US cents.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 63.43 US cents, little changed
from Tuesday's finish of 63.47 but barely holding above key
support levels at 63.20 after plumbing new depths in midday trade.
</P>
<P>
A rampant US dollar and plummeting Asian currencies have kept
the local unit on its toes, with traders ascribing it to a "sell
the rally" mentality.
</P>
<P>
The Australia dollar was last at these levels in October 1986
when it was recovering from its historic post-float low of 57.10
US cents in July 1986.
</P>
<P>
IBJ Australia senior foreign exchange dealer Darrin Stewart
said current support levels for the Australian dollar at 63.20 US
cents would depend on the US dollar/yen exchange rate and
developments in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"There is no real support. If the Aussie doesn't go down today
it'll go down later in the week," Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless there is any significant news out from the Fed or some
concerted intervention, the Aussie will continue to probe lower
levels over the next few days," he added.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian currencies led by the Indonesian rupiah
continued their fall to record lows against the US dollar
following Indonesian President Soeharto's budget speech on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, Acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer refused to comment
on the value of the Australian dollar, saying the Australian
economy is well set to weather the Asian storm.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is in good shape," Fischer said in response to
questions from journalists.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 84.61 yen,
from 85.83 Tuesday and at 1.1634 marks, from 1.1628.  
</P>
</TEXT>
