<HEADLINE> Roundup: Exchanges Between Judicial Departments of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Exchange of visits and cooperation
 between judicial departments of Macao and China's inland areas in
1997 promoted mutual friendship and understanding, contributing
to the smooth transition in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Six Chinese judicial delegations visited Macao last year. They
included such high-level delegations as the Chinese Prison Society
 and high-ranking procurators of Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
In return, Macao sent four high-level delegations to Beijing,
Xi'an and Hangzhou. Director of the Macao Justice Department
Carlos Dias, President of the Supreme Court of Justice Manuel
Antonio Maduro, Assistant General Procurator Antonio Simoes
Redinha, and Chief Commissioner of the Anti-Corruption and
Anti-Illegal Administration Commission of Macao Luis de Mendonca
Freitas joined the delegations.
</P>
<P>
Besides the exchange of visits, legal experts and lawyers of
both Macao and the inland jointly hosted several seminars last
year on the new Code of Criminal Procedure of Macao, intellectual
property rights, and legal issues in the transitional period of
Macao.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the Lawyers Association of Macao jointly hosted
a "Pearl River Delta Law Conference" with its counterparts in Hong
Kong and neighboring Guangdong province, South China, last
November. Lawyers of Macao, Hong Kong, Zhuhai and Shenzhen met for
the first time to exchange views on legal issues.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a number of books on the study of Macao's legal
system and laws were published in the inland or Macao with
cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the exchange of visits and cooperation
between Macao and the inland in the past year covered a wide range
of issues.
</P>
<P>
"The increased contacts in the legal field between the two
places will not only help promote understanding and friendship, it
is also helpful to a smooth handover of power and the prosperity
of Macao," said an analyst who prefers not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The localization of law, he said, remained one of the major
issues in the bilateral contacts. That will help promote the
successful localization of law in the transitional period.
</P>
<P>
As 1999 approaches, further contacts between the two sides are
needed to pave the way for a smooth handover of power.  
</P>
</TEXT>
