<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimming Worlds Farewells Unlimited Underwater Kick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The 8th world swimming
championships will farewell the unlimited underwater kick that
many say has revolutionized the butterfly stroke, and which
Australia's Michael Klim used to break the world 100m record in
October.
</P>
<P>
The International Swimming Federation (FINA) decided days
before the world championships to limit underwater butterfly to 15
meters from the start and from turns.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Dennis Pankratov of Russian dived for
35-to-40 meters of the first 50 meters in the 100m butterfly at
the Atlanta Olympics, where he set the previous world record of
52.27 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Klim dived for 25 meters to break that record, setting the new
mark of 52.15 seconds at Australia's world championship trials in
Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
American Misty Hyman, currently ranked world No.1 in the
women's 100m butterfly, has reached today's fame mainly by kicking
underwater.
</P>
<P>
Of the current world long-course butterfly records, only two
were not set using the underwater kick -- the women's 100m and
200m marks set by American Mary Meagher in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will come into force on March 6, FINA announced
after January 5 congress.
</P>
<P>
The other rule changes include the reintroduction of
semi-finals in swimming, which were last conducted in 1976. How
this rule is to be applied will be decided by the FINA Bureau
later.
</P>
<P>
World records for 50m backstroke, breaststroke and butterfly
will now be recognized, as it already the case for competitions in
world short-course championships, according to the world swimming
ruling body.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been opposing the inclusion of 50m races
in the events except freestyle. It's also against the
reintrodution of the semi-finals and the limit of the underwater
kick.
</P>
<P>
Hyman's coach, Bob Gillett, had been lobbying for the unlimited
underwater kick prior to the Perth Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"The underwater fly or fish kick is innovative, it's exciting.
It's fun. And it does fall under the current definition of
butterfly," he said in November's issue of the Swimming World.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
