<HEADLINE> Feature: Night Schools Draw a Crowd in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region is no longer an isolated place whose residents are more
eager to learn Chinese and foreign languages as a means to
communicate with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
So far, 15 private schools have opened in Lhasa, capital of
Tibet. In addition to languages these schools offer courses in
computers, driving and Tibetan handicrafts. Students are from all
walks of life, and most are local residents.
</P>
<P>
Lhasa Language School, located on Bargor Street in the city's
downtown area, is one of the biggest.
</P>
<P>
Six one-story classrooms are crowded with Tibetan students
every night, with 200 bicycles parked outside.
</P>
<P>
"Without language skills, you can't find a good job
now. Chinese is very useful, so I decided to learn it here," said
Zhouga, an 18-year-old Tibetan girl.
</P>
<P>
From Nagchuzur County, Zhouga baby-sits during the day and
studies at night. It is her first attempt to study Chinese and she
hopes to find a better job.
</P>
<P>
The school offers students courses in such languages as
Tibetan, Chinese, English, German, Japanese and French. It now
offers computer courses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
