<HEADLINE> Employers in Malaysia Urged Not to Reduce Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Malaysian
trades union Congress (MTUC) Wednesday urged employers in Malaysia
not to reduce workers but to work out a mutual arrangement so that
workers can still keep their jobs amid the current economic
setback faced by the country.
</P>
<P>
MTUC President Zainal Rampak said in a statement that employers
should first consult the trade unions before embarking on any
downsizing, retrenchment or closure exercise.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that through negotiation and dialogue sessions
between workers and employers, a mutually acceptable arrangement
can be worked out so that workers can keep their jobs and there
will be industrial peace and harmony," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MTUC chief said companies employing non-unionized workers
should first approach the Human Resources Ministry for
consultation before initiating any measures that might affect
their workers.
</P>
<P>
He said the MTUC had written to Human Resources Minister Lim Ah
Lek on January 1 asking him to convene a meeting of the National
Labor Advisory Council to examine recent developments.
</P>
<P>
It would be unwise for companies to prematurely lay off workers
or close down their operations in Malaysia under the pretext that
it was no longer viable to do business here, as Malaysia was not
the only one affected by the foreign exchange problem, Zainal
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
