<HEADLINE> Tibetan Handicrafts Exhibition Opens in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The First Tibetan Handicrafts
Exhibition opened in Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong Province, today.
</P>
<P>
On diplay at the three-day event, sponsored by southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region, are more than 1,000 ethnic
articles, such as scroll paintings, carpets, ethnic dress,
utensils, medicines and sculptures made of leather, stone and
wood.
</P>
<P>
The world's largest Tangka, 45 m long and 35 m wide, is the
most precious and attractive article at the exhibition. Tangka is
a kind of Tibetan scroll painting. Pictures of Buddha, Buddhist
tales, portraits and lives of historical figures and eminent monks
are the major subjects.
</P>
<P>
Visitors can also learn about Tibet's history, culture and
social development through abundant photos and video
products. 
