<P>
Dealers said the further plunge of the share prices reflected
investors' concerns over the continuing fall of regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
They said that the fall of the currencies was attributed to the
spill-over of negative sentiment over an austerity budget for
Indonesia's next fiscal year, which was unveiled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 202.66 million units,
valued at 369.89 million Singapore dollars (about 208.98 million
U.S. dollars). Declines again overwhelmed advances by 329 to 43,
while 240 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Engineering was the most actively traded counter
as it registered a turnover of 12.05 million units. It was
followed by DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land which had
7.56 million shares traded. RHB Capital was next with 6.54 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Asean Fund led the gainers of the day as it rose by 50 cents to
finish at eight Singapore dollars. Roth Singapore increased by 35
cents to end at 8.85 Singapore dollars. GP Bat picked up by 22
cents to close at 4.52 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 2.6 Singapore dollars to end at 31 Singapore dollars.
Parkway Warrant98 fell by 69 cents to close at 61 Singapore cents,
while MISC Foreign was 66 cents lower to finish at 1.81 Singapore
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
