<HEADLINE> Tibet Sets up Remote-Sensing Research Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A remote-sensing research center
began operations today in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony to mark the establishment of the center, Xu
Mingyang, vice-chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Region, said the
center will play a significant role in the region's policy-making
for surveying resources, assessing crop output, protecting the
environment, opening up land resources, and monitoring and
preventing natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
He said the center will lay a solid foundation for the
formation of the region's dynamic information service system of
basic resources and the environment.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade the Tibet Meteorological Department and
other institutes have employed remote-sensing technology to launch
survey projects of the Yarlung Zangbo and Lhasa rivers as well as
land resources in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The remote-sensing technology has also been applied to the
monitoring of forest fires, snowstorms and the growing conditions
of forage grass. It has resulted in conspicuous social, economic
and ecological effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
