<HEADLINE> Zambia's State of Emergency Worries EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
deeply concerned about the continuing state of emergency in
Zambia, particularly the arrest of opposition leaders, The Post
paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The EU, in a statement issued by the outgoing Luxembourg
Presidency on all EU members and released in Lusaka today, urged
the Zambian government to either charge or release opposition
leaders, namely former president Kenneth Kaunda and Dean
Mung'omba of Zambia Democratic Congress, according to the
independent paper.
</P>
<P>
"The EU urges the government of Zambia to complete their
investigation into all those detained under the current state of
emergency and in particular leaders of the opposition parties
with all speed and either charge or release them," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, leader of the country's largest opposition party, the
United National Independence Party, was arrested last December
and later shifted to house arrest for alleged involvement into an
abortive coup last October.
</P>
<P>
While Mung'omba was detained by police two days after
President Frederick Chiluba declared the state emergency
following the foiled coup on October 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a response to external pressures to push for the release of
opposition leaders, Chiluba Monday denounced donor countries,
particularly Britain and the U.S., over their opposition to his
state of emergency and detention of Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
He also advised other African heads of state to be wary of
"colonial masters" whose reoccupation, he said, was "to divide
and rule." 
