<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Industry Becoming Powerhouse (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station of east China's Zhejiang
Province and the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station in south China's
Guangdong Province have been operating safely and their combined
annual power output is three times the equivalent of China's total
power generation in 1952.
</P>
<P>
The two nuclear power stations have not only alleviated
electric power shortages in east China and Guangdong, but also
have transmitted a large quantity of power to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The two nuclear power stations, which are now under commercial
operation, have both been economically viable. Per-capita annual
output of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station is more than 4
million yuan, while per-capita annual output of the first phase of
the Qinshan Nuclear Power Station exceeds 700,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Practice has proved that the investment return rate of nuclear
power development is not lower than that of coal-burning electric
power stations. The nuclear industry with power development as its
main feature has become a new powerhouse of China's national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the second and third phases of Qinshan, and the
Ling'ao and Lianyungang nuclear power stations are all in full
swing.
</P>
<P>
By early next century China's nuclear power generating capacity
should amount to 9.2 million kilowatts and, by then, earnings from
sales of nuclear power are expected to reach 30 billion yuan a
year. The industrial structure of the country's nuclear industry
will be further improved at that point, coupled with improved
economy and technology.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power now contributes one percent of China's total
power output, but nuclear power makes up 17 percent of the world's
total power output. Clean and highly efficient, nuclear power has
advantages in the market based on a range of factors such as
energy structure, the environment and transportation.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, Fujian and Jiangxi provinces of east China, Hainan
Province of south China and Hunan Province of central-south China
have all been active in making preparations for constructing their
own nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
In the next century, China is expected to have a significant
development in nuclear power. By the year 2010 China's nuclear
power-generating capacity will reach 20 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
And, by 2020, China's nuclear power-generating capacity should
reach 40 million kilowatts and the proportion of nuclear power in
the country's total power production should increase to five
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Killer Disease Named as Rift Valley Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Medical experts have said that
the mysterious disease which has claimed more than 300 lives and
killed hundreds of livestock in northeastern Kenya is likely to
be the Rift Valley Fever.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted Maina Kahindo, Head of the
Communicable and Vector Borne Control Division in Kenyan Health
Ministry, as saying that specimens of samples so far analyzed
"strongly identify the mysterious killer disease to be Rift
Valley Fever".
</P>
<P>
He said "our local analysis and that of South Africa's
Reference Laboratory strongly point to the Rift Valley Fever."
</P>
<P>
Kahindo noted that a field surveillance team comprising
medical and veterinary experts and entomologists had been
established in the affected areas in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, two leading virologists in the
country are still analyzing samples for various haemorrhagic
fevers whose symptoms are bleeding from body orifices and "that
is why we are yet to conclusively say what this epidemic is."
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Fever is a viral disease transmitted by mosquitoes
and is predominantly found in domestic animals. It can also
affect human beings exposed to heavy infection by direct contact
with infected animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1977, it suddenly flared up as a human infection in Egypt
involving 200,000 people, out of whom 600 died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0175 </DOCNO>
