<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Situation Stabilized in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The outbreak of cholera in
Mozambique has been brought under control since late last
December, the health authority said.
</P>
<P>
Avertino Barreto, Deputy Director of the National Health
Department was quoted by Noticias Paper as saying in Maputo
Tuesday that since the last three deaths on December 27, no
further deaths have reported.
</P>
<P>
The official said only five patients were hospitalized Monday,
compared to between 200 to 300 daily at the height of the
outbreak last November.
</P>
<P>
The cholera outbreak in Mozambique has claimed 267 lives since
it broke out last August. About 9,144 patients were registered.
</P>
<P>
Barreto also disclosed that the authorities have closed one of
the two cholera treatment centers at the Maputo Central Hospital
and another in the suburban area, as the number of patients
decrease.
</P>
<P>
He, however, warned that some of the illegal food markets
closed by the government may stage a comeback and that the
unclean food sold at the markets is a major cause of the cholera
outbreak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
