<HEADLINE> PNG Relief Supplies Halted After Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Relief food supply to one of
the worst affected drought-stricken provinces in Papua New Guinea
has been suspended after the looting and vandalism of a supply
truck, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Trucking operator Pagini &AMP; Transwest, in a fax to rice supplier
Trukai, said it had halted all food deliveries from Mt. Hagen to
Enga province and that the delivery would not be resumed until the
safety of its workers was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
A truck carrying 25 tons of rice and 25 tons of cooking oil was
stopped and looted by a large crowd of people while on its way to
the Engan capital of Wabag on Monday, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
The truck was escorted by police who were overwhelmed by the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a new report by Australia's aid agency AusAID said
more than one million Papua New Guineans were now facing food
shortages because of the drought.
</P>
<P>
Trukai's marketing manager Neville Whitecross said 135 tons of
food supplies were in Mt. Hagen waiting to be delivered to the
province.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the looting incident, self-proclaimed chairman of a
local drought relief committee Ronald Rimbao said 70,000 people in
the Wapenamanda district of Enga were facing starvation.
</P>
<P>
He said his people would stage sit-ins along the highway and
stop vehicles unless the government acted.
</P>
<P>
Police have made no connection between Rimbao's threats and
Monday's incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
