possible foreign involvement, which included the collusions of
their diplomatic missions with the coup plotters in the foiled
coup plot," said Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, quoted by press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
The actual details of the involvement was being investigated,
Ikimi told the corps of African ambassadors Tuesday in the
capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, the coup suspects, including Chief of
General Staff Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and 11 others, intended to
assassinate Head of State General Sani Abacha, some key military
officers and prominent civilians both in and out of the
government.
</P>
<P>
He said the motive of the coup suspects was to disrupt the
military regime's transition to civil rule program through the
alleged coup, which commenced three months before to government
took action to foil it on December 21 last year.
</P>
<P>
"They had also intended to put in its place a new extended
program in addition to the conspiracy to loot the nation's hard
earned foreign reserves," Ikimi said.
</P>
<P>
He told the diplomats that the suspects would be tried
according to the Treason and Other Offenses Act of 1986, the
current law under which treason and other offenses committed by
military and civilian collaborators are tried.
</P>
<P>
The suspects would have ample opportunity to defend themselves
and obtain, if they so desire, legal representation from the
corps of military lawyers, in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Nigerian government briefed
foreigners on the botched coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Audio-video clips on the alleged coup plot have been shown to
top military officers, cabinet members, state administrators and
representatives of traditional rulers.
</P>
<P>
Media executives are reported to be given access to the
electronic documentary materials soon.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi also gave details of the alleged coup plot during
Tuesday's meeting with the newly arrived U.S. Ambassador William
Twaddel, who reportedly could not offer any commitment on the
United States' position on the event.
</P>
<P>
The United States, among some other foreign countries, has
called for open and fair trial of the coup suspects.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Abacha urged Nigerians not to introduce
ethnic sentiments into the alleged coup issue, apparently a
response to speculations following the fact that most of those
arrested in connection with the coup plot are from the Yoruba
ethnic group in the west.
</P>
<P>
Everybody must strive to ensure national security and the
smooth execution of the transition program now than ever before,
Abacha told a delegation of traditional rulers from nine eastern
states.
</P>
<P>
The Abacha administration is scheduled to hand over power to
an elected government on October 1 this year, according to the
transition program.
</P>
<P>
It was disheartening that the persons involved in the coup
plot, who used to be his close confidants, would aim to derail
the program they had actively participated in, the head of state
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
