<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's State Enterprise Reform to Take More Challenges in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: To closely follow the development of China's
economy and the reform in economic life, we are offering a column,
Observation of China Economy, which will analyze and comment on
the major economic events and trends in the country on a weekly
basis. The column will be available on Wednesdays, except for New
Year's Day of the Chinese Lunar Calendar (Jan. 28). This is the
first of a series of columns.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- As Chinese people step into the
Year of Tiger, the nickname for the year 1998 on the Chinese Lunar
Calendar, the country's far-reaching reform in state-owned
enterprises will enter a special period featuring both great
opportunities to make historical breakthroughs and rough
challenges from the old economic structure.
</P>
<P>
By resorting to reform means such as regrouping, mergers and
bankruptcy, China will revamp its 5,500 debt-ridden large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises during the 1998-2000 period.
The reform will be launched first in 2,000 such enterprises this
year. Two million workers will be laid off.
</P>
<P>
Because of the more mature market economy and a growing trend
toward economic globalization, all the problems affecting
enterprise reform have "deep roots" in the present system and are
not easy to resolve, said Wang Zhongyu, minister in charge of the
State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
"However, we have no time to postpone the solution of these
problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest State Statistical Bureau (SSB), all
87,000 state-owned enterprises generated 34.2 billion yuan in
profits during the first 11 months of last year, an increase over
the same period in 1996. But the number of enterprises losing
money accounted for one-third of the total. The losses of such
enterprises was a staggering 70.5 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's State Enterprise Reform to Take More Challenges in 1998 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government intends to stem losses in the
state-owned sector within three year. The reform goals include
establishing a modern enterprise system with firms running in the
red, encouraging mergers to form powerful conglomerates and moving
redundant workers to other jobs.
</P>
<P>
This unprecedented reform will begin with the textile industry,
which had suffered losses for three consecutive years and employs
1.8 million workers.
</P>
<P>
To make the industry into cost-efficient, the government will
reduce the 4.8 million spindles in the coastal provinces in east
China this year and relocate 600,000 workers to other jobs. The
industry expects to reduce the losses by three billion yuan
compared with 1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of spindles to be reduced and workers to be laid off
account for 50 percent of the total under the three-year reform
plan of the government.
</P>
<P>
Chinese economists said that, compared with other industrial
sectors, the textile industry suffers the most severe financial
trouble, the highest losses and the most workers. The textile
industry reform will be significant in the country's efforts in
other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will allocate 40 billion yuan to write
off the bad debts of the large and medium-size state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The country will also encourage the public listing of
enterprises with good performance to raise 100 billion yuan on
domestic and overseas stock markets. All funds raised by the
enterprises will be used in adjusting the product mix, launching
technical renovation and acquiring other enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist of SSB, said that the smooth
macro-economic operation in 1997 -- in addition to a relatively
abundant supply of energy, raw materials and farm produce and a
better fiscal situation -- provided solid guarantee for future
reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's State Enterprise Reform to Take More Challenges in 1998 (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the other hand, steady growth in the national economy this
year should be ensured with a "significant breakthrough" in
state-owned enterprise reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the increasingly rough reform and readjustments in
the economic system and a possible small slump in the gross
domestic product (GDP) growth rate this year, some negative
factors could be enhanced and threaten the ongoing enterprise
reform. These include financial trouble for the state-owned
enterprises, an increase in unemployed workers and poverty, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Qiu said the government should pay close attention to the
change in these factors in the future.
</P>
<P>
The government should help debt-ridden enterprises adjust their
enterprise structure rather than simply issuing loans, and to
improve the management style and competitive edge of products,
according to Wang Tongsan and Liu Shucheng, two prominent
economists with the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
In enterprises in which products have little or no sales value
and debt is increasing, government loans should be used as living
stipends for workers rather than an investment in production.
</P>
<P>
The government has given the nod to these economists' ideas.
An official with State Economic and Trade Commission said that in
addition to helping enterprises earn more profit, the government
will speed up construction of a modern enterprise system this year
and promote the application of a shareholding system in the
state-owned sector. A number of enterprise groups also will be
established through mergers and re-organization.
</P>
<P>
Without an efficient enterprise system, the losses in
enterprises could be a lasting headache for the government, Qiu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
