<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Rebounds After Hitting New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso rebounded
after touching a new of low of 46.50 pesos against the US dollar
in Wednesday's trading on the Philippine Dealing System (PDS).
</P>
<P>
The peso was averaged at 44.419 to the greenback at noon on the
PDS, the country's electronic currency exchange, and closed at
45.30 pesos to the dollar with a turnover of 203 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank raised the overnight borrowing rate by a
percentage point to 12 percent and said this will help the peso to
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
The demand for the greenback also eased after the central bank
opened a temporary facility under which it sells short-term
non-deliverable forward contracts through the banks, traders said.
</P>
<P>
With the new low of 46.50, the peso has depreciated by about 76
percent since the currency crisis hit Southeast Asian nations in
early July last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
