<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deaths in Vietnam's Road Accidents Remain High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Casualties in road accidents in
Vietnam remain high in 1997 with an average of 31 people killed
every two days.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5,680 people were killed in road accidents last
year, slightly down from the figure of 5,900 in 1996, according to
government statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of injured people rose to 21,905 in 1997
from the 21,700 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-five percent of the road accidents in 1997 were caused
by bad driving.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also showed that the number of cars on Vietnam's
roads went up by 12.3 percent in 1997 and that of motorbikes
clogging the streets rose by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to traffic police, there are around 5 million
motorbikes in Vietnam compared to just 418,000 cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
