<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Enterprises in Guangxi Get Rid of Random Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The practice of government
departments and official institutions imposing unauthorized fees
on state enterprises has been abolished in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
These random charges, which mainly came from arbitrary fund
raising, fines and requests for donations, amount to more than 250
million yuan annually, sources said. They have long been a sore
point for the enterprises in the region and have weakened their
ability to compete in the market.
</P>
<P>
A recent study in the region found 1,481 different charges,
1,131 of which were directed at the State-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi will abolish 377 more random charges early this year,
reducing enterprises' annual expenditure by as much as 100 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of a nationwide campaign to get the
money-losing state-owned sector out of difficulties in three
years, as called for by the central government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
