<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Iraqi National Assembly Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government and
people deeply sympathize with Iraqis who have suffered from United
Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin offered this remark here this morning
during his meeting with a delegation of the Iraqi National
Assembly led by Saadoun Hammadi.
</P>
<P>
"We have always held that the remaining issues of the Gulf War
should be settled at an early date on the basis of the relevant
resolutions of the United Nations," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president expressed the hope that Iraq would
continue to cooperate with the United Nations, properly handle and
improve its relations with the countries concerned with the goal
of winning more sympathy and support from the international
community and, eventually, that sanctions would be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang extended a welcome to his Iraqi guests, saying that their
visit will further deepen the understanding and cooperation
between the Chinese National People's Congress and the Iraqi
National Assembly and play an active role in the promotion of
friendly relations and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that this year marks the 40th anniversary of the
establishment of Sino-Iraqi diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
China is satisfied with the smooth growth of bilateral ties and
is ready to further increase friendly cooperation with Iraq on the
basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi spoke highly of China's rapid economic development and
its support to Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has maintained friendly relations with China for a long
time and hopes that such relations will grow even further, Hammadi
added.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary leader also briefed Jiang on the situation in
Iraq under the U.N. sanctions.  
</P>
