<HEADLINE> Farming Resumes in Tanzania after Heavy Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in several
flood-stricken regions in Tanzania have resumed farm activities
on highland areas after heavy rains subsided, the Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an official from the Mwanza Regional
Commissioner's office as saying that they have directed people to
embark on agricultural activities in highland areas to cushion
the effect of food shortages as a result of the heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Mara and Shinyanga regions said that local
authorities have urged people to prepare seeds ready for planting
when flooded areas dry up.
</P>
<P>
The Tabora Regional Commissioner, Stephen Mashishanga said
Tuesday that local residents have started reinforcing their farms
in both lowland and highland areas.
</P>
<P>
The food situation in the region is expected to improve after
the resumption of train services between Tabora and Mpanga.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) has
committed over 80,000 U.S. Dollars in assessing the 1997/98 crop
season in 14 regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
FAO representative Sulayman Sait M'boob said in Dar es Salaam
Tuesday that three teams will use hired planes and other vehicles
to carry out the task so as to come up with a thorough assessment
report.
</P>
<P>
Flood and drought have conspired to hit Tanzania last year,
making more than 1.4 million of this east African nation's 30
million population suffering from food shortage.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the FAO provided over 2.65 million U.S. Dollars for
drought relief and livestock disease control to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological departments have asked people to take
precautionary measures as excessive seasonal rains linked to El
Nino weather phenomenon may last till April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
