<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Lesotho Police Cooperate to Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South African police have
reached an agreement with their Lesotho counterpart to work
together to stop cross-border stock theft raids, local daily
Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Police and officials from the foreign affairs departments of
the two countries met yesterday to discuss a cross-border
incident on New Year's day, in which at least seven people were
shot and hacked to death, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A team of policemen from Lesotho and South Africa would
investigate the incident, said a South African official.
</P>
<P>
South African farmers were alleged to have crossed into
Lesotho through KwaZulu Natal Province and stolen goats and
sheep. Lesotho residents retaliated, resulting in clashes that
left at least seven people dead.
</P>
<P>
Residents said up to 11 may have been killed, but mist and
harsh terrain were hampering the search. Police said it was
possible some of the bodies had been carried away. 
</P>
