<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Banks Targets Inflation Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
assured the public it will be able to achieve 6.5 to 7.5 percent
inflation rate this year despite financial market turmoil, the
Philippine News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted central bank governor Gabriel Singson as
saying that any inflationary pressures from the adjustment in the
peso-dollar rate resulting from the currency crisis will be
matched by a series of effective monetary measures to keep the
inflation rate acceptable.
</P>
<P>
The central bank already adopted the necessary measures that
will help stabilize prices in the market, Singson said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that latest preliminary data on base money and
reserve money showed an annual growth rate of between 15 to 23
percent, adding that domestic liquidity had stabilized since
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
He added that the monetary authorities will continue to rely on
open market operations and will continue to coordinate closely
with the private sector to contain any unnecessary infusion of
funds into the system.
</P>
<P>
The average inflation rate for 1997 declined to only 5.1
percent from the 1996 rate of 8.4 percent despite the currency
crisis which swamped across the Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has projected full-year inflation
rate at 6.5 to 7.5 percent for 1998, taking into account the
likely wage and oil price adjustments and further depreciation of
the peso.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
