<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Shortage Hits Zambian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign exchange shortage hits
capital Lusaka, as a result of low earnings from metal sales and
supply halt by the country's biggest foreign exchanger earner,
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), The Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sam Equamo, ZCCM corporate affairs manager, in a response to a
press query on the shortage of foreign exchange on the market,
confirmed that the supply of foreign exchange onto the market has
been constrained by low earnings from copper sales, said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The price of copper is currently at its lowest in many years.
The company is obliged to use the limited foreign exchange
earnings to service its debt and any surplus thereafter is then
released to the market," said Equamo.
</P>
<P>
The development has resulted to a critical shortage of foreign
currencies, mainly the U.S Dollars, in both the commercial banks
and bureax of change in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Some bureax have restricted the sale of the foreign currency
to customers who are willing to buy at 1,610 Kwacha per Dollar
while the buying price two weeks ago was 1,500 Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Zambia, the central bank, was initially the
supplier of foreign exchange from ZCCM to the financial market
but since Zambia introduced the liberalized exchange control
policy several years ago, it gave authority to the conglomerate
to retain its earnings and sell to the commercial bank's when it
deemed fit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
