<HEADLINE> KANU Urges Tough Action on Threats to Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) has asked the Kenyan government to deal
strictly with any threats to the country's peace, stability and
unity, the Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Following meetings held separately on Tuesday by the KANU
National Executive Council and the party's Parliamentary Group,
KANU First Vice-Chairman George Saitoti said that the two organs
urged Kenyans to reject any calls aimed at threatening the
country's peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The two organs made a decision that KANU would hold elections
before the end of this year, which were put off last year with
most party members expressing fear that elections may break the
party as it prepared for the just concluded General Election.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government yesterday sacked all the striking nurses
and laboratory technicians who have been on strike since November
28 last year for higher pay.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of New Year, President D. A. Moi asked the striking
nurses to resume duties on January 1 as the government was
looking into their grievance. However, they dismissed the call.
</P>
<P>
A statement signed by the Director of Medical Services, James
Mwanzia, said that the nurses, health workers and laboratory
technicians who refused to resume duty by January 1, this year,
had been sacked.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government announced the formation of a
Task Force to review all laws governing the health services in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
