<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Shanghai Residents Marrying Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners seem to be losing
favor with the young women of Shanghai, the largest manufacturing
and financial center in China.
</P>
<P>
The city had a boom period in foreign laisions during the early
nineties, but now the city's economic development is offering
young women other opportunities for a better life.
</P>
<P>
The number of women in the city who married foreigners in 1997
was down 9 percent from the previous two years, according to the
city's civil affairs bureau.
</P>
<P>
And, what these marriages lost in numbers, they gained in
quality as the difference in age between husbands and wives was
less dramatic than before.
</P>
<P>
In more than half the marriages last year, the age gap was only
three to five years, and it was rare to see a young woman going to
register a marriage with a man twice her age.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that Shanghai's young women have more radical views
about their marriage partner and fewer of them view marriage as
the pathway to a better life or a way to see the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Inter-racial marriages began again after 1978, when China
started its reforms and opening up to the outside world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
