<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Zoo Greets Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- As the Spring Festival,
China's traditional lunar new year, is coming up, Shanghai Zoo is
permeated with a festive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
A picture exhibition on tigers is being on show at the zoo to
help people know tigers and save them. It specifies relations
between human beings and tigers, tigers inhabiting in different
countries, tigers' current conditions and how they are endangered.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, co-sponsored by the Zoo and the Wildlife
Conservation Society, is the first of its kind ever held in
China.
</P>
<P>
Each tiger at Shanghai Zoo eats an average of seven kilograms
of beef or mutton and drinks two big bottles of milk
daily. Animals keepers often feed the tigers with some
calcium-rich and multi-vitamin tablets to keep them in good
health.
</P>
<P>
To greet the season, Shanghai Zoo plans to exhibit some albino,
such as white toad, white soft-shelled turtle, white snake, and
white yaks that recently became "residents" of the zoo. The
animals were either caught by farmers in suburban areas or bought
by urban residents from pedlars.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will also have the opportunity to watch giant pandas,
little monkeys, and kangaroos during the festival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
