<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Denied Control of Radio, TV Transmitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The office of the High
Representative in Bosnia-Herzegovina has rejected a request by the
hard-line Bosnia Serb leadership in Pale to give back the control
of radio and television transmitters, which are currently held by
NATO.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Hina, the Croatian News Agency, the
office of the High Representative also dismissed Serb accusations
that transmitters had been damaged due to poor maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Technicians of Serb radio and television stations have been
granted regular access to the transmitters so that they can take
care of their maintenance, said Rida ttanashari, spokesman for
the office of the High Representative in Sarajevo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Radio and television transmitters in eastern Bosnia were put
under the control of the Stabilization Force (SFOR) after the
studio in Pale had ignored the request of the international
community to change its editing policy and ban party influence
from the state media.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnia Serb television and radio program is being broadcast
exclusively from a studio in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
However, Attanashari announced that an international supervisor
would be sent to Banja Luka as well, to monitor whether
professional media standards are being observed.
</P>
<P>
At a session held on Monday in Bijeljina, Northern Bosnia, the
incumbent government of the Republika Srpska, which is made up
exclusively of the members of the Serb Democratic Party (SDS),
asked SFOR to give back the studio control.
</P>
<P>
They further said that the next session of the Bosnian Serb
Assembly, to be held on January 12, would be broadcast if their
request was met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Car Maker Expects 30 Percent Drop in Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's national car
manufacturer -- Proton -- expects a 30 percent drop in sales in
1998 given the weak market conditions, Chairman Mohd Saleh Sulong
of DRB-Hicom Group to which Proton belongs said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Proton is expecting export sales to improve
tremendously as it plans to focus its effort on this area, he said
at a press conference after a ceremony in Port Klang, about 40
kilometers west from here, to mark the sending off of the first
batch of 300 cars to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Proton cars are now exported to 50 countries including Turkey
with a total of 164,153 units exported as of December 31, 1997.
Out of the 50 countries which Proton exports its cars to, only 42
are active, according to Mohd Saleh.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, Proton is targeting to export 53,000 units compared
with 32,000 units in 1997. Mohd Saleh said that the export volume
of 53,000 units expected for the new financial year beginning
April 1998 will be achieved through its present core markets and
also from five new markets which Proton hoped to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
Apart from penetrating new markets, which will provide good
volume for Proton cars, he said that special efforts would also be
focused on reviving non-active markets.
</P>
<P>
He said the European market would still continue to be an
important market for Proton which will embark on launching new
products from 1999 to the year 2000 as planned earlier.
</P>
<P>
For the new financial year, Proton hopes to be able to sell a
total of 200,00 units both at home and abroad, compared with a
total of 210,000 units sold in the current financial year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
