<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find Wildlife In Desolate Lop Nur (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists and zoologists
have found that there is in fact wildlife in the desolate wastes
of Lop Nur in the Tarim Basin in the northwestern part of China.
</P>
<P>
A flock of wild geese, which was seen there in October by a
group of petroleum geologists, were flying south, only about 20
meters above the ground in a lateral formation.
</P>
<P>
The team had been in Lop Nur off and on over an eight-month
period and, according to Kong Zhongxiang, the deputy head of the
team, they were wondering how the geese could be in such a place
without any water.
</P>
<P>
Lop Nur is in China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region and
occupies an area about the size of the Republic of Korea. It used
to have China's second largest inland lake but it turned to desert
after the Tarim River shifted course more than 2,000 years
ago. Since then, it has been regarded as a "zone of death".
</P>
<P>
One monk who passed through Lop Nur about 1,500 years ago on a
mission to Western Asian commented in his travel journal that the
place "had no birds or animals. All that can be seen are dry human
bones."
</P>
<P>
Kong and his team also saw Mongolian gazelle and wild camels
during their exploration of a 7,000-sq.km. area in eastern Lop
Nur. He says that wild camels can often be seen on both sides of
the dry Shule River course, where there are a dozen springs.
</P>
<P>
"The pools of water are shallow and clear, but too salty to
drink," he reports, but says they saw a shrub-like plant rich in
protein which seemed to be the camels' favorite food.
</P>
<P>
Zoologist Gu Jinghe, who has visited Lop Nur a number of times,
says that his team saw wild camels repeatedly and that he believes
about 300 wild camels live in Lop Nur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find Wildlife In Desolate Lop Nur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kong's team stayed at a tent camp with their vehicles,
surrounded by barren wastes, devoid of trees and grass.
</P>
<P>
Then, in October, they saw larks flying near the camp.
Curiously, the birds, which are known for their lilting song, all
seemed to be mute. It turned out that the birds had followed the
vehicles which were carrying water supplies, and could manage to
live for no more than 20 days, after which they would die of
thirst.
</P>
<P>
But what surprised them most were the two crows they found
there that were as big as wild geese, Kong says. The zoologists
only collected forty specimens of animals and birds in all, says
Gu, noting that the wildlife is scattered in small groups.
</P>
<P>
And there are only a few wild camels, Tarim red deer, and Tarim
rabbits, about a hundred in all. They live mostly in a valley in
the eastern part and in dried swamps in the southwestern part
around a cluster of weather-beaten mud holes. Hardly any wildlife
is seen in the dried river basin that covers a 25,000-sq.km. area.
</P>
<P>
"On average, there's only one animal for every 1,000 sq.km. of
ground, and in this sense, Lop Nur is still a zone of death," Gu
concludes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
