<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Condemns Misuse of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A commentary, carried by
Rodong Sinmun, the largest newspaper of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), Wednesday condemned the abuse of
sanctions in the world.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that the DPRK welcomes the statement,
issued by the United Nations Third Committee in Geneva recently,
which criticized some big powers for imposing sanctions on other
nations in a bid to achieve their own political goals.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Third Committee, in charge of human rights and social
issues, also pointed out that sanctions hurt the basic right of
survival of the people in the sanction-hit countries, and proposed
to set up a special body to monitor the use of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that in 1990s, the U.N. Security Council
imposed a series of sanctions upon the countries including Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, many sanctions were proceeded from the considerations
of national interests of one or two big powers in the Security
Council, especially the United States, the commentary added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been so active in making use of the so-called
human rights issues and terrorist activities to wantonly impose
sanctions upon other countries that a saying of "American-style
sanction" has emerged in the world, said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
Many unjustified sanctions, including the implementation of the
U.S. D'amato Bill and Helms-Burton Law, intensified the social and
economic instability in many countries and regions, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the commentary noted, "the sanctions, a product left
over by the old era and a tool used by a few big powers to seek
their own interests, is strongly condemned by the whole world."
</P>
<P>
Activities against sanctions have even been dynamic in the
U.N. arena, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
