<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Party Accepts Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Opposition leader Raila Odinga
has accepted the results of the December 29 General Election and
congratulated President Daniel arap Moi on his victory, according
to a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The National Development Party leader, who was third in the
just ended presidential race, sent a congratulatory letter
Tuesday to President Moi, saying that it was in the interests of
the nation and Kenyans to accept the outcome of elections.
</P>
<P>
Odinga dropped his earlier rejection of election results and
demand for repeat elections within 21 days which he made jointly
with Democratic Party Chairman Mwai Kibaki last Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Odinga said that everyone should "join hands in
the challenging task of reforms and economic reconstruction of
our country."
</P>
<P>
His party would collaborate with other democratic forces in
pursuit of a people-centered reform package within and outside
Parliament, he added.
</P>
<P>
Odinga is the second key presidential loser to accept the
election results following the acceptance by Ford-Kenya Chairman
Kijana Wamalwa whose position is fourth in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki who came second in the race and Charity Ngilu of Social
Democratic Party who is fifth have so far not accepted the
outcome of the election.
</P>
<P>
President Moi was proclaimed winner of the elections by
Kenya's Electoral Commission last Sunday and sworn in for his
final five-year term Monday during a colorful ceremony at Uhuru
Park in Nairobi. 
</P>
