<HEADLINE> Beijing Has More Than One Million People Buying Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that
450,000 more people in China's capital invested in the stock
market in 1997, bringing the number of investors there to 1.1
million.
</P>
<P>
Most new investors in the second half of 1997 were middle-aged
or young professors, scientists, and technicians, while in the
first half of the year, most were middle-aged or elderly, and were
jobless, many of them former employees of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In April and May, when the stock market had some obvious rises,
there were at least 50,000 new investors each month and 3,000 per
day during the busiest days.
</P>
<P>
After the country adopted new stock market regulations, fewer
people became interested in the stock market and an interest rate
cut in October had little impact on the market.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts here say they believe this indicates that
investors are more mature and aware now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
