<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Increase Exports to Avoid Regional Monetary Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is trying to speed up the
bureaucratic processing of imports and exports to avoid the
effects of the regional monetary crisis dramatically affecting the
national economy, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam expects to earn about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars from
exports while spending about 2.77 billion dollars on imports in
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
A senior official was quoted as saying the trade ministry and
other relevant organizations needed to promptly allocate quotas on
key exports in order to facilitate the signing of long-term sales
contracts among traditional and new partners.
</P>
<P>
Government office director Lai Van Cu said everything should
be done quickly to avoid the affects of the current monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The country is facing many difficulties in the first quarter of
this year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The main exports in the first quarter will consist of 3.2
million barrels of crude oil, 850,000 tons of coal, 180,000 tons
of coffee beans, 50,000 tons of rubber latex, 700,000 tons of
rice, 260 million U.S. dollars worth of seafood, 350 million in
textile and garment products and 300 million pairs of shoes.
</P>
<P>
These exports are expected to increase by 29 percent compared
with the same period last year, an amount equal to 23 percent of
the government plan for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, import value is expected to rise by just three
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Joint-ventures with foreign investment are scheduled to earn as
much as 230 million dollars from their exports, which will account
for nearly nine percent of all exports.
</P>
<P>
Products imported by foreign invested joint-ventures are
expected to amount to 700 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
