<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold Wave, Fog Cause Havoc in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Normal life and business in
Bangladesh have nearly come to a standstill due to days of cold
wave and fog all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The country's national airline, Biman, had canceled all its
domestic flights and delayed all its international flights due to
the poor visibility caused by the thick sheet of fog, press
reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On the Dhaka-Aricha highway, a seven-kilometer-long queue of
vehicles was formed as dense fog disrupted ferry service in two
routes from the Aricha and Nawa ghats.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Aricha, 80 kilometers west of Dhaka, said the
ferries there experienced a most sever traffic congestion as about
6,000 vehicles remained stranded there awaiting to be ferried
across the rivers of Padma and Jamuna.
</P>
<P>
Some 45 people have died so far in the current cold spell that
started about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The government has started distributing warm clothes in the
cold spell-hit districts, mainly in the northern and western parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Disaster Management and Relief Ministry have so far
allocated 11,600 quilts, and the prime minister's Relief Fund has
also distributed a large number of winter clothes in 22 districts,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Weather experts said the sever cold associated with the
blinding fog was likely to continue for one or two days. "Another
cold wave is likely in the middle of the month," they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
