<HEADLINE> Italy Sees 2.5 Percent Growth in GDP in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Finance Minister Vincerzo
Visco said Tuesday that the country's economy was likely to grow
by about 2.5 percent next year, above the government's forecast of
two percent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Italian TV, Visco said a recent upsurge in consumer
demand coupled with new tax breaks for bourse investment and other
concessions for the construction industry should power the economy
to "robust" higher-than-expected growth.
</P>
<P>
Higher growth figures next year will help Italy's efforts to
cut its deficit and gross domestic product (GDP) ratio, already
lower than the target set for joining the European economic and
monetary union.
</P>
<P>
A surge in growth, also fueled by the Bank of Italy's recent
interest rate cut, should also make it likely for Italy to achieve
a significant dent in its debt and GDP ratio, which has only
recently started to come down towards the Maastricht limit of 60
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
