<HEADLINE> Kurdish Immigration not An Invasion: Italian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Italy will look with favor upon
Kurdish requests for political asylum, Prime Minister Romano Prodi
told German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in a telephone call, the
prime minister's office announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the long conversation described as "cordial and
constructive," Prodi confirmed Italy's commitment to maintain
control of its borders as required under the Schengen Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The asylum requests will be examined on an individual, not
collective, basis, Prodi told Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders stressed the importance of the conference in Rome,
scheduled for Thursday. The conference will focus on the recent
flood of Kurdish immigrants and fighting criminal elements
involved in the illegal trafficking of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Brussels, EU leaders are preparing for
Wednesday's inter-governmental conference which will also center on
the issue of Kurdish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are expected to discuss border controls, ways of
fighting the falsification of identity cards and passports and
efforts to counteract the involvement of organized crime in the
illegal movement of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"We'll try to determine if border controls are effective enough
or if they need to be strengthened," European Commissioner for
Foreign Affairs Hans van den Brock said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
