<HEADLINE> Thailand's Energy Consumption Remains High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's energy consumption
last year was estimated to have soared by 7 percent, although the
country's economic growth was close to zero, the Bangkok Post
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
That reflected inefficient energy consumption in the country,
said Pongpisit Viseshakul, director of energy conservation at the
National Energy Policy Office (NEPO).
</P>
<P>
Although the Thai people's awareness of energy conservation has
risen, they now need to learn how to save energy in their daily
lives, Pongpisit said.
</P>
<P>
To help educate the public, NEPO will finance a short
television documentary to show how the public can save oil. The
footage will be followed by others on saving electricity and
water, Pongpisit said.
</P>
<P>
In most developing countries, energy consumption correlates
with economic growth, but Thailand has been an exception, the
director added.
</P>
<P>
Between the mid-1980s and the mid-1990s when the Thai economy
was booming with an average growth rate of around 7 percent, the
country's energy consumption jumped 11-12 percent annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Home Appliance Market Competition Intensifies In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Domestic home appliance
companies are feeling mounting pressure from overseas counterparts
in market competition, today's China Daily quoted a recent survey
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chinese makers hold at least 70 percent of the market in color
televisions, washing machines, refrigerators, air-conditioners,
video compact disc (VCD) players, electric cookers, microwave
ovens and freezers, said the survey conducted by the Chinese
Society of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, their advantage of low product prices has little room
for manoeuvre after multiple price wars in recent years, warned
Zhang Zehou, the society's secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign appliance manufacturers, backed by their
strong financial and technological clout, are eyeing a larger
slice of the Chinese market, and many of them are opening
production bases in the country, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which covered 600 department stores in 121 cities
in China, showed that home appliance sales in those stores
accounted for 39 percent of the country's total in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that foreign companies had seized 96.5 percent
of the video cassette player market and 53 percent of the hi-fi
equipment market. They are likely to pose a stronger challenge
this year to Chinese refrigerator producers, Zhang predicted.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and foreign appliance manufacturers are launching
cut-throat competition for a solid position in the market,
supported by dazzling TV advertisements. Their common efforts to
expand production capacity have led to serious oversupply. And
this, in turn, has intensified competition.
</P>
<P>
Refrigerators and VCD players may become the two major areas of
market competition in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rivalry over digital video disc (DVD) players, the latest
generation of video appliances, has already started in earnest,
while the fight for a bigger share of traditional products
continues.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign firms are now preparing to present DVD players
priced at around 2,000 yuan, slightly more expensive than a VCD
player. "DVDs are likely to enjoy unprecedented development in
1998, adversely affecting the booming VCD market," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Urban families remain the major purchasing power for home
appliances. But rural areas are emerging as a potential market,
Zhang reminded producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Tax in Southern Chinese Province Up Significantly in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Income tax in Guangdong
Province, one of China's more developed areas, rose 40 percent in
1997, making the province the highest payer of income taxes in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong had collected 3.2 billion yuan (385 million
U.S. dollars) in income taxes by the end of November and it
expects to meet 1997's goal of 3.5 billion yuan, according to the
provincial tax bureau.
</P>
<P>
The province's income tax revenues account for 14 percent of
the country's total. They have grown for the second year, since
tax reforms were carried out in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
