<HEADLINE> Investments in Philippines Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The continued regional financial
crisis has slowed down investments in the Philippines as some
big-ticket projects stayed on the sidelines, latest data released
by the Board of Investment showed.
</P>
<P>
Registered investments in the last quarter of 1997 fell by 81
percent to 54 billion pesos (1.3 billion US dollars) from 298
billion pesos (7.2 billion dollars) in the corresponding period of
the previous year, the data showed.
</P>
<P>
However, total investments registered in 1997 reached 554
billion pesos (13.5 billion dollars) from 395 billion pesos (9.6
billion dollars) in 1996, 40 percent higher than 400 billion pesos
(9.8 billion dollars) of the government's target for the year.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the total investments was due to huge projects
registered during the first half of the year, the data said.
</P>
<P>
The government is aiming for a goal of 700 billion peso (17
billion dollar) investments for 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
