<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Reforms Agriculture for EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will speed up the
introduction of European Union (EU) agriculture standards and
legislation reforms in preparation for accession to the union,
Bulgarian Agriculture Minister Ventsislav Vurbanov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By March 15, 1998, Bulgaria must launch its Cooperation for
Accession programme to prove to the European Commission that it is
working hard to overcome shortcomings in its agriculture,
Vurbanov told a news conference at the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government's priorities should include building a modern
export-oriented agriculture, improving consumer protection,
completion of land reform, and legislative reform, Vurbanov said.
</P>
<P>
The short-term 1998 programme prioritizes legislative
reform. Bills on fodder, seeds, planting materials, fertilization
and on the selection and breeding of animals, have been drafted in
compliance with EU standards and will be introduced in parliament
in 1998, Vurbanov announced.
</P>
<P>
The implementation deadlines for these commitments will be set
in a medium term programme. Bulgarian experts said any delay in
meeting these obligations would mean an end to the Phare
programme, under which the EU would increase its financial
assistance two-to-three fold by 2003-2004, to around 70 ECU per
capita in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
A European Commission view that Bulgaria seemed to be
experiencing the greatest difficulties in its legislative
integration into the EU was also stated at Tuesday's news
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
