<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Establish New Plantations For Timber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to establish 504
hectares of new plantations in eight districts this year to meet
the country's fuel-wood and timber requirements and to conserve
environmentally viable areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year it had established plantations in 260 hectares giving
preference to local species, according to Sri Lankan forest
department sources Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the department has launched a massive project to
convert pine plantations into those of local species through under
planting, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
So far, maintenance work had been carried out in 64,000
hectares of plantations established in 15 districts and trials
have been done to evaluate plant species to identify suitable
species to be grown in the plantations in these areas.
</P>
<P>
A vegetative propagation unit will be established soon to
produce better quality seedlings this year, said the sources,
adding that permanent sample plots will be maintained to obtain
data required for better management of the these plantations.
</P>
