<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Employment Rate to Rise Moderately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Italy's employment rate will rise
to 59.1 percent in 1998 and 59.3 percent in 1999 from 59 percent
in 1997, said a survey issued by the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the improved rate will still be the lowest in the
Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized countries, said the 29-member
OECD which expects its average employment rate to climb to 70.7
percent in 1999 from 70.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Italy's employment rate would also be lower than the European
Union's average of 67.1 percent in 1999, it added.
</P>
<P>
Within the OECD, only Turkey, Mexico and Hungary's employment
rates were forecast to be lower than Italy's in 1999, which would
stand at 55.1, 55.4 and 57 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the OECD forecasts, in 1999, the highest
employment rate of 83.9 percent will emerge in the Czech Republic,
while 80.5 percent in Denmark, 79.2 percent in Japan and 77.6
percent in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
