<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Issuance of Higher Interest Rate Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The continued fall of the peso
may compel the Philippine Central Bank to consider the possibility
of floating bills that carried extremely high interest rates of 48
percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Manila Chronicle Wednesday quoted Central
Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as saying that issuing so called
"Jobo-type" bills is the ultimate solution if the currency crisis
persists.
</P>
<P>
"Jobo-type" bills were issued during the height of the
country's foreign exchange crisis in the 1980s when inflation hit
64 percent by then central bank governor whose nickname is "Jobo".
</P>
<P>
The central bank had to offer interest rates of as high as 50
percent to stabilize the economy which was reeling from high
inflation and low international reserves.
</P>
<P>
The bills proved successful in containing inflation but it
contracted the economy as many businessmen were forced to shut
down due to high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"I hope I do not have to be the one to do it," Singson said,
adding the Philippines may not have the ability to absorb such
high rates of bills.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank chief said the move is one of the options
of the government.
</P>
<P>
"If this happens everyday (the fall of the peso), what do you
do? We cannot keep supplying the market. One possible option is
Jobo type bills, or Gabby bills or somebody's bill," Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Singson said President Fidel Ramos has called for another
nationwide economic summit this month to discuss possible
solutions to the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We need to rebuild our international reserves," Singson said,
citing that the central bank's gross international reserves had
dwindled to about 9 billion U.S. dollars at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the need to jack up dollar reserves of the country,
he said concerns over tight credit availability and high interest
rates and the unstable peso top the list of the concerns of
monetary authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
