<HEADLINE> Dolphins Aground and Die In Mass In Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and one dolphins
have died in mass as they ran aground on a beach at Turtle Island,
state of Anzoategui in Venezuela, the Environment Ministry said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Natives, along with tourists, tried to make some dolphins
go back into the sea but in some cases their efforts was futile.
</P>
<P>
A group of Venezuelan policemen tried to return one of the
acquatic mammals to the sea but the dolphins got back to land
just to die three hours later.
</P>
<P>
The investigation about the massive death of dolphins is
carried out by experts from the National Fund of Fishing
Investigation and the Museum of the Sea in Cumana.
</P>
<P>
The dolphins that died on the sand of Caldera Beach are of
the Strenella Attenata kind, which is rare to be found in
Venezuelan waters. The species is 2.02 meters long.
</P>
<P>
The dead mammals weighed an average of 100 kilograms and 80
percent were females.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Ministry ordered the setting up of a commission
to further investigate the cause of the mass death of dolphins.
</P>
</TEXT>
