<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Improves Public Health Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province has made good progress in developing basic public health
services in recent years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, 115 counties and cities, or 90.5 percent of
all the province's total, have introduced basic public health
services.
</P>
<P>
At present, 12 out of the 17 counties and cities which are
threatened by snail fever have eliminated the disease, which has
been also put under effective control in the rest five counties
and cities.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of malaria was also put under control within five
cases reported among every 10,000 people in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the incidence of diseases, Yunnan has sped up the
construction of epidemic prevention facilities in border areas,
and in other places across the province.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, 16 out of the province's 17 prefectures and cities and
90 counties in the province had launched cooperative programs on
maternity and child care, with the mortality rate of infants and
pregnant and lying-in women decreasing drastically.
</P>
<P>
There are now 0.84 medical workers for per thousand people in
the province and the average life expectancy has reached 67 years.
</P>
<P>
The province's input in medical and health services exceeded
one billion yuan in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Raises Grain Output by Developing Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province, the country's most important grain reserve base, is to
turn itself into an even more powerful grain-producer by
developing water-efficient irrigation in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2000, the eight million ha of cultivated land are
expected to produce an additional 7.5 billion kg of grain each
year. The move is to raise the province's annual output to 37.5
billion kg.
</P>
<P>
To realize the goal, provincial governor Tian Fengshan urged
the whole province to develop water conservancy projects,
particularly water-saving irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 2.8 million ha of farmland, or over one-third of the
province's total, were threatened by the severe and persistent
drought, according to a China Daily report today.
</P>
<P>
A record 3.4 billion kg of grain, worth 5.4 billion yuan, was
estimated to be damaged by drought in 1997 in Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
To counter the challenges, water resources authorities plan to
bring more than 1.3 million ha of arid farmland under effective
irrigation in the next three years. Half of this will be
accomplished by adopting various water-saving irrigation
techniques, including building 50,000 new irrigation wells and
9,600 other watering supply projects.
</P>
<P>
The newly improved irrigated land is expected to yield 4.5
billion kg of grains or 60 percent of the increase expected by the
end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The other 40 percent will be produced with the help of such
measures as using low-cost dribble-watering to replace the
outdated, openly cut trenches, which wasted more than 60 percent
of the total water used in irrigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
