<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministries Ready to Face Festival's Travel Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Railways and the
Ministry of Communications are ready for the transport blitz
around the Spring Festival of the Chinese Lunar New Year, which
falls on January 28.
</P>
<P>
The annual travel peak usually comes when millions of farmers
working in cities return to their villages for family reunions
before the festival and return to their jobs afterwards.
</P>
<P>
This year's peak transportation period will last 50 days,
from tomorrow to February 26, sources from the two ministries
said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways plans to carry 139.3 million
passengers during the travel peak, up 3.4 percent from last year's
figure. And about 36.97 million passengers are expected to travel by
long-distance trains, up 11.7 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicts there will be 10 busy railway lines
during the period, including the Beijing-Guangzhou Railway,
Beijing-Shanghai Railway, Beijing-Kowloon Railway,
Lianyungang-Lanzhou Railway and Shanghai-Hangzhou Railway.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways has allocated 6,000 extra carriages
for the coming peak period, ministry officials said. Overall 34
pairs of passenger trains are ready for handling emergencies in
Chengdu, Changsha and Nanchang, which are the major hubs through
which migrant workers move.
</P>
<P>
During the upcoming season, the country's road network is
expected to carry 1.64 billion passengers, up 5.2 percent from
last year. Water transport departments will handle 38 million
passengers, nearly the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to add more direct long-distance and charter
bus and charter boat services in Guangdong, Zhejiang, Jiangsu and
Fujian provinces and Shanghai and Beijing cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
