<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Shut More Overseas Trade Centers, Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will temporarily shut
eight commercial offices and four trade centers abroad from March
31 to save money, according to the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also defer opening new offices as part of the
government's drive to cut spending. Last year it closed seven
commercial offices and four trade centers.
</P>
<P>
The planned closures could trim 195.44 million baht (3.9
million US dollars) from 953 million baht (19.06 million dollars)
earmarked for representation abroad this year, and as much as 371
million baht (7.4 million dollars) from 1999 fiscal year, the
ministry was quoted Wednesday by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry currently has 47 commerce offices abroad, of which
those in Bucharest, Stockholm, Colombo, Lisbon, Tashkent, Kiev,
Mexico City and Cairo will be closed.
</P>
<P>
Of the trade centers, those in Lyons, Atlanta, Warsaw and
Shanghai will be closed.
</P>
<P>
Trade centers in Kunming and Guangzhou in China and the Hague
in the Netherlands would be supervised by the Thai Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Plans for an office in Bombay, India, would be put on hold
until the Thai economy recovered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
