<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renminbi Yuan Unlikely to Be Devalued: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The renminbi yuan is unlikely to
be devalued even though the sharp depreciation of currencies in
neighbouring countries will inevitably affect China's export
trade, according to an authoritative source.
</P>
<P>
A financial official who declined to be identified said the
world market should maintain its confidence in the renminbi rate's
stability. The marginal changes in the rate that follow the market
demand and supply are normal, he was quoted as saying in today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The official said China is enjoying speedy growth in foreign
trade and a constant influx of foreign funds. There has been a
glut in the foreign exchange market because of the favourable
international balance of payments.
</P>
<P>
The situation is expected to continue as the country moves to
improve the competitiveness of its export products and encourage
foreign investment by further cutting tariffs. China's nearly 140
billion U.S. dollars of foreign exchange reserves would buffer
fluctuations in the balance of payments, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the official noted, China's foreign trade firms
have sharpened their non-price competitiveness in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China had more than 40 billion US dollars in trade
surplus and added 30 billion dollars to foreign exchange
reserves. Therefore, lowering the renminbi's value artificially
would only spark rifts between China and its trade partners, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He disputed the opinion that the financial crisis sweeping
Southeast Asia since last July was elicited by the integration of
the renminbi's two-tier exchange rate in 1994. "The view is
incompatible with the facts," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
China unified the market and the official exchange rates of the
renminbi in 1994, causing the exchange rate of the yuan against
the US dollar to depreciate to 8.7 to 1.
</P>
<P>
He said the normal exchange rate of the renminbi actually
dropped only seven percent after the integration, instead of 33
percent or 50 percent as some people had predicted.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, devaluation is not the key element behind China's
export boom in recent years, the source said. It is technical
upgrading and improvement of efficiency that have done the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
