<HEADLINE> International Community Continues to Play Role in Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations official in
Croatia said here Tuesday that the international community will
continue to play a role in the region when the term of the
transitional administration expires.
</P>
<P>
William Walker, a member of the U.N.'s Usremsko-Baraniskoj
transitional administration in Croatia, made the remark at a press
conference after meeting with Serbian President Milan Milutinovic,
Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
Walker said the international community would not abandon the
region after January 15, 1998, the expiration date for the
transitional administration. The civil police of the U.N. and the
representatives of the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe will remain to supervise the works of the Croatian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Walker and Milutinovic also discussed the
situation in the Usremsko-Baraniskoj region and other issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Milutinovic praised Walker for his personal role in
fulfilling the commitments of the transitional administration. He
also expressed the hope that the international community would
continue to play a supervisory role in the region. 
</P>
