<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Calls for Developing Nuclear Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Experts in Kazakhstan are
calling on the government to develop nuclear power at the turn of
the century, the Kazakhstan Pravda reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted experts as saying that by the end of 2010
the country will face a serious energy crisis.
</P>
<P>
The experts said, in a just-concluded symposium on nuclear
power, that the thermal power plants, which are the major
electricity suppliers of the country, will not be able to meet the
demands of economic growth. An energy shortage would loom large in
southern industrial cities, they added.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan boasts abundant uranium and the extraction of the
radioactive element is at much lower cost compared with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Using nuclear power was conducive to preventing greenhouse gas
emission, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
They said the new-type nuclear power plants, which have
multi-layer security guarantees, would be able to avert a
Chernobyl-type incident.
</P>
<P>
The explosion of the No. 4 reactor at Ukraine's Chernobyl power
plant in April 1986 was the worst civilian nuclear catastrophe to
date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
