<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Mixed Message on Low Australian Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A weaker Australian dollar
meant Australian products would be cheaper and become more
competitive in the world market, though local people, rich and
poor, will be hit by price rises of everyday household items,
local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Exporters of Australian-manufactured goods or raw materials,
such as mineral products, will be benefited from a low dollar, Tim
Blue, an economist, wrote in The Australian, the country's leading
newspaper, on the falling local currency.
</P>
<P>
The prices of Australian major export earners, such as gold,
copper, aluminum, nickel and zinc have been tumbling, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Gold reached a new 18-year low, shedding 6.70 U.S. dollars an
ounce to 282.70 U.S. dollars an ounce after weekend comments by
U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan were interpreted by
financial markets as a warning that deflation could become a
problem for the global economy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar, which started at 80 U.S. cents in March
last year, slipped 63.35 U.S. cents Tuesday, the lowest level
against the greenback in more than 11 years following a gold price
in freefall and continuing chaos in Asian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Frank Gelber, an economist, told The Australian that five years
of 65 U.S. cents an Australia dollar is what he would like to see.
</P>
<P>
"It helps our exporters and it helps our import-competing
industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
A weaker Australian dollar should boost sales and deliver
higher incomes for farmers, The Age, a Melbourne-based daily,
said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a spokesman with Australia's National Farmers
Federation as saying beef exports competing against U.S. farmers
would have a strong price advantage and it could help reduce
potential lost sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The size of the Asian market is shrinking, but the size of our
share of that market could increase", the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A lower Australian dollar would help sell wool, particularly in
emerging markets, such as India and eastern Europe, Greg Evans,
executive director of Wool Council, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
But the Sydney Morning Herald argued the Australian dollar's
slump meant reduced demand for Australian exports and a higher
chance of products being dumped in Australia.
</P>
<P>
It said prices of everyday household items are set to jump by
up to 20 percent over the next six months as a result of the
falling Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Essentials such as clothes and food will not be spared, and
will rise by as much as luxury items such as European cars,
expensive sporting equipment and white goods, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
