<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Copenhagen's Little Mermaid Decapitated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Little Mermaid statue,
located on the waterfront of Danish capital of Copenhagen, was
decapitated overnight in a new attack, the second one since 1964.
</P>
<P>
Police said Tuesday that the head of the small bronze figure
was sawn off by unknown culprits and there were no clues.
</P>
<P>
Divers scoured the harbor bottom for the head on Tuesday, but
had not found it.
</P>
<P>
The world-famous Little Mermaid statue first lost her head in
1964 and her arm was sawn off in 1985. They were replaced as the
mould was well preserved.
</P>
<P>
The statue, a masterpiece of renowned sculptor Edward Eriksen,
was finished in 1913. It has been a symbol of Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
It depicts the young heroine of Denmark's 19th-century author
Hans Christian Anderson's famous fairy tale, "The Daughter of The
Sea." 
</P>
