<HEADLINE> Philippine Former Defense Chief Forms New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Former Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa has registered with the Commission on
Elections a new political party to serve as his vehicle in his
presidential bid in May.
</P>
<P>
De Villa is standard bearer and chairman of the Party of
Democratic Reform (Reporma). Former agriculture secretary Roberto
Sebastian, now representative to the World Trade Organization, is
party president.
</P>
<P>
Reporma will be the lead party in the United Third Force, which
will be formed in alliances with other political parties, local
press reports Wednesday quote De Villa as saying.
</P>
<P>
De Villa quit the ruling party and declared to form the "United
Third Force" last December to continue his bid to run for
president after losing President Fidel Ramos' endorsement as the
ruling party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
The former defense chief told around 2,000 followers Tuesday
when he registered the new party that he will continue the battle
against the prevailing political system that relies on patronage
and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Third Force is an alternative to both
popularity politics and patronage politics.
</P>
<P>
"We will pursue the fight against this rotten system. It is
time to launch reforms in a government that neglected the people,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
