<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Economy Expected to Grow 5.2% In 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The renewed dynamism of
the Mexican economy permits a prediction of at least 5.2 percent
growth of Gross Domestic Product in 1998, the Center of Economic
Studies said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
nevertheless, in order to achieve a lasting and sound economic
expansion for 1998, the country needs to undergo some structural
changes in its law system to further foster productive
activities.
</P>
<P>
The study says that the major pending issues is to put
into place a legal frame that guarantees respect to property
rights and physical security to people and their belongings.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect awaiting reform is the improvement of the
tax-collecting system and deregulation of business-making.
</P>
<P>
The experts of the center said that the main economic
"engines" this year will be consumption and therefore expansion
of domestic markets, investment and exportation.
</P>
<P>
This dynamism, the document says, could create one million jobs.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve that in the mid-term the government has
to start loosening its belt-tightening economic policy and begin
rising salaries but maintaining a restrained pace as to keep inflation
down to 13 percent, necessary condition for currency stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
