<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan had approved
Iraq's distribution plan of food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies on Monday night, the Office of the Spokesman for the
Secretary-General announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The distribution plan for phase three under the oil-for-food
program was approved last night, and the Secretary-General had
informed the president of the Security Council as well as the
Iraqi Government about the approval, the spokesman's office said.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq, which has been under UN
economic sanctions since it invaded Kuwait in 1990, is allowed to
sell two billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy
necessities for its people. (Annan-Iraq-Food Plan)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Pakistan Tuesday announced their readiness
to make joint efforts to bring peace to the war-torn Afghanistan,
Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The stance of the two neighbors of Afghanistan was announced in
a meeting between Pakistani special envoy on Afghanistan issue
Iftikhar Murshid and his Iranian counterpart Alaeddin Boroujerdi
Tuesday afternoon. (Iran-Pakistan-Afghanistan)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is set to talk with France over
a French deal with Iran in the energy section, which is involved
in punishment of a French oil company in accordance with a
U.S. sanctions act, the State Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin told reporters that Under Secretary of
State Thomas Pickering was to leave for Paris late Tuesday to
discuss with French officials "Iraq and Iran and other subjects."
(US-Iran-France)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Tuesday defended its
involvement in a trilateral exercises with Israel and Turkey in
the eastern Mediterranean, saying it was only a "humanitarian
operation."
</P>
<P>
"This exercise is a humanitarian exercise. It's about a
scenario in which a ship is suffering and needs assistance in a
humanitarian operation," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told reporters. "We think it's certainly appropriate for the
United States, Israel, and Turkey to engage in that."
</P>
<P>
But countries in the Middle East regarded the exercise, named
"Reliant Mermaid," as a threat to the region's security as the
exercise indicates a growing military ties between Israel and
Turkey and these countries were irked by U.S. involvement in the
exercise. (US-Mideast-Exercise)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Some 40 percent of South Korean companies are planning
to cut their manpower due to the current financial crisis, said a
survey issued by the Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 39.8 percent of the surveyed 376 companies and banking
institutions said they are planning to slow down their operations
while 42.5 percent said they will curtail personnel by up to 100,
and 15 percent is to cut at least 300.
</P>
<P>
Of the surveyed, 92.3 percent consented the need of workforce
reduction while 63.6 percent will opt for a smaller paycheck as
part of downsizing. (South Korea-Cut Labor Force) 
</P>
</TEXT>
