<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's Cotton Output At Halt due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen of the
Colombian textile industry will import at least 50,000 tons of
cotton this year to meet its production needs if the fiber
plantations in the Atlantic coast do not recover.
</P>
<P>
This was warned on Tuesday by a group of specialists including
weather experts and economists.
</P>
<P>
Fear of some Colombian cotton growers for predicted harmful
effects of the El Nino climatic phenomenon and violence by
guerrillas caused cotton fields to be so scarce.
</P>
<P>
In El Cesar, one of the cotton-producing regions of Colombia,
farmers did not want to sow the land last year on 580 cotton-due
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Similar situations emerged in the regions of La Guajira and
Magdalena, where cotton is a traditional product.
</P>
<P>
Colombian experts on weather have warned that the El Nino has
not but begun its "maturing" stage and that its inclemencies are
to be felt until June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
