<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Protects Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Steps are being taken to protect
cultural relics in the pathway of Beijing's Ping'an Avenue, which
is under construction, according to Wang Hongnian, an official
with the Municipal Cultural Relics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
There are a dozen historical sites along the avenue, which runs
from Dongsishitiao Overpass on eastern Second Ring Road to the
Chegongzhuang Overpass on western Second Ring Road, parallel to
Chang'an Avenue, one of the city's most famous streets.
</P>
<P>
The sites include the northern gate of Beihai, an imperial
garden built in the Jin Dynasty (1115-1234), and the former
residence of Dr. Sun Yat-Sen, pioneer of the Chinese democratic
revolution, where he lived from the end of 1924 until his death in
1925.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that in order to keep the historical sites intact,
parts of the avenue will be narrower or will have to make a
detour, and that any relics unearthed during the construction will
be well-protected.
</P>
<P>
He said that anyone who violates the cultural relics law during
this work will be penalized.
</P>
<P>
The 6,893-m. avenue is expected to cost two billion yuan (about
240 million US dollars) and will be completed by August 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
