<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Holds Phone Talks With European Leaders on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has
held telephone talks with leaders of Austria, France and Italy on
how to tackle illegal immigrations in Europe following a recent
influx of Kurdish refugees from Turkey to Italy.
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, Kohl
had telephone conservations with Chancellor Viktor Klima of
Austria, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of France and Prime Minister
Romano Prodi of Italy today, as well as with French President
Jacques Chirac Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held amid increasing fears in Germany that the
1,300 mainly Kurdish refugees who streamed to Italy's southern
coast in the last two weeks as well as more refugees who are
reportedly en route would finally slip into Germany via Austria
and France.
</P>
<P>
Also today, German Interior Minister Manfred Kanther made it
clear that Germany, which had already taken in about 350,000
Bosnian war refugees since 1992, would not tolerate another major
illegal immigration of foreign refugees.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that Germany had already sent hundreds of
reinforcements to the police forces at its southern and western
borders in order to stem the feared influx of Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he accused Italy of failing to tighten its external
border against illegal immigrations as required by the European
Union open-border Schengen agreement which Italy joined in
October.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1985 Schengen accord, seven western European states
-- Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal
and Spain -- have already scrapped their normal interior border
controls in a bid to allow freedom of movement within the group.
</P>
<P>
Italy and Austria are also due to do the same by the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
Fearing that the open-border arrangements would encourage more
illegal refugee movements into Germany, some German politicians,
including the interior minister of the Lower Saxony state, Gerhard
Glogowski, have demanded that the Schengen accord be suspended
until Italy tightens its asylum laws.
</P>
<P>
Kanther, however, indicated today that he did not favor
suspending the accord and that it still remained a valid way to
promote common security and freedom of movement in Europe.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the German Interior Ministry said Monday that
Germany would urge its European partners to intensify the use of
possibilities provided by the Schengen accord to intercept illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of police officials from Schengen countries is due to
be convened Thursday in Rome to discuss the latest refugee issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
