<HEADLINE> NZ Dollar Falls Sharply against US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar
dropped by over 80 U.S. cents in trading with the Greenback on
Tuesday, ending at a three-year low of 56.56 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Kiwi dollar was dragged down by the lower Australian
dollar, which sank to an 11-year low against the stronger U.S.
dollar. The U.S. dollar is now seen as a safe-haven currency in
the face of the continued economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Kiwi has now fallen 20 percent against the U.S. dollar
compared with one year ago, when it peaked at more than 71 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
But experts think the decline in the NZ dollar does not mean an
immediate boom for the NZ exporters.
</P>
<P>
They noted that many exporters have protected themselves from
the harm of the rising Kiwi dollar in the past year by locking in
a set value for the currency over periods of up to one year.
</P>
<P>
This means that it will be months before the weaker dollar
brings benefits to some exporters, the experts predict.
</P>
<P>
However, they agreed that the sharp fall in the NZ currency
against the U.S. dollar will help offset the expected impact of
lower demand in Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
