<HEADLINE> South Korea Financial Trouble Affects NZ Log Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's massive log
export trade to South Korea may drop away significantly in coming
weeks or months, according to Fletcher Forests, one the two big
suppliers to that market.
</P>
<P>
A local report Monday quoted the company as saying on Tuesday
that log exports, worth of tens of millions of dollars a year,
were in doubt because of importer's problems with South Korea's
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Fletcher Forests is refusing to ship logs without letters of
credit from buyers and buyers are finding it hard to get those
bank orders to assure exporters of payment.
</P>
<P>
The report said if the South Korean market dried up, it would
have a serious impact on Fletcher Forests, although the company
was trying to diversify into other markets and process more logs
in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Radio NZ also reported on Tuesday that Fletcher Forests was
considering to stop cutting trees if the present situation in
South Korea continued.
</P>
<P>
This would put several hundred jobs in jeopardy, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter last year, 57 percent of NZ log exports
went to South Korea, totaling 975,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Carter Holt Harvey is the other big supplier of logs to South
Korea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
