<HEADLINE> US to Talk With France Over Iran Energy Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States is set to
talk with France over a French deal with Iran in the energy
section, which is involved in punishment of a French oil company
in accordance with a U.S. sanctions act, the State Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin told reporters that Under Secretary of
State Thomas Pickering was to leave for Paris late today to
discuss with French officials "Iraq and Iran and other subjects."
</P>
<P>
He gave no details on the discussed issues. But analysts here
believed that the issue of imposing U.S. sanctions on the French
energy company Total SA and two other companies from Malaysia and
Russia for a 2 billion dollar gas project in Iran would come up
first on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Pickering's talks with French officials come at a time when
Washington is waiting for a statement from Iran's President
Mohammed Khatami in his interview with CNN scheduled on Wednesday,
as his statement might affect U.S. policy toward the Islamic
republic.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration was said to be eager to hear what
Khatami would say and what kind of a clearer sign would give for
the possible warming ties between the two feuding countries.
</P>
<P>
Although Washington does not expect anything dramatic from the
Iranian president, it still hopes Khatami could conceivably
designate a negotiator and propose a date and time for talks with
U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Pickering's talks with French officials thus will have
potential impact on relations between the United States and Iran.
</P>
