<HEADLINE> US Criticizes Mexican Judge's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
criticized the release by a Mexican judge of a man accused of
fatally shooting an American businessman during a robbery in
Mexico City last month.
</P>
<P>
"We unequivocally condemn this judge's decision," State
Department spokesman James Rubin said, noting that the man had
confessed his guilt to local prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Alonso Gonzalez Sanchez was one of five men arrested on
December 30 on charges he had targeted foreign tourists and
residents for robberies after they boarded taxis.
</P>
<P>
Police said all five men confessed to robbing Peter Zarate, a
U.S. real estate executive who formerly lived in California, on
December 15.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Judge Maria Claudia Campuzano decided that Gonzalez
Sanchez be released. The judge was quoted as saying that Gonzalez
Sanchez is "a modern Robin Hood."
</P>
<P>
Rubin noted the Mexico City prosecutor's office has publicly
denounced the judge's action and plans an appeal. It also is
seeking to detain the released men on other unrelated charges.
