<HEADLINE> Ethanol Reduces Greenhouse Gas Emissions: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Corn-based ethanol outperforms
significantly conventional and reformulated gasoline in terms of
greenhouse gas emissions and energy use, according to the U.S.
Renewable Fuels Association (RFA).
</P>
<P>
A study shows that a blend of ethanol and unleaded gasoline may
reduce fossil energy use by 50-60 percent and greenhouse gas
emissions by 35-46 percent compared with conventional fuels, said
the RFA in a report today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures of Argonne National Laboratory, the RFA said the
comparison took into account ethanol's total production costs,
including corn farming, ethanol production, transportation and
distribution and ethanol combustion in motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The United States produces a total of 1.58 billion gallon
ethanol annually mainly using corn grown in Illinois, Iowa,
Nebraska and Minnesota states, the RFA said.
</P>
<P>
The use of methanol as an alternative auto fuel is among the
hot topics being discussed by U.S. auto makers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
