<HEADLINE> U.S. Selects Career Diplomat as Ambassador to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will most probably choose veteran diplomat Jeffrey Davidow as the
next U.S. ambassador to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Although he refused today to confirm the selection, White House
spokesman Mike McCurry strongly hinted that Davidow, who is
currently the assistant secretary of state for Latin American
affairs, is the right person.
</P>
<P>
"The president's been interested in finding someone who would
ably represent the interests of the United States government at a
time in which we are building a very strong partnership with the
government of Mexico and, of course, Assistant Secretary Davidow
has been involved in exactly that," McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported today that Davidow was named in an
"action memo" sent to Clinton for final approval.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the process, which is obviously very far along, will
be completed shortly," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has not had an ambassador to Mexico since
former Oklahoma Republican Jim Jones left the post in June.
</P>
<P>
Former Massachusetts Governor William Weld was named to fill
the vacancy by Clinton, but Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee blocked a Senate vote on the
nomination. 
