<HEADLINE> US Companies to Invest More in Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. companies will spend more
on information technology to increase their competitiveness, a
survey found.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six percent of chief information officers (CIOs) polled
said they plan to expand their budgets by an average of 20 percent
on information technology in 1998, said RHI Consulting in a press
release from California today.
</P>
<P>
RHI, a leading specialized staffing service firm in the United
States, said hardware purchases and software upgrades stand high
in companies' budget plans, capturing 37 percent and 26 percent of
their 1998 budgets respectively.
</P>
<P>
The survey on the 1,400 CIOs in the U.S. concluded that
companies across all industries see new technology as a priority
in their strategies to upgrade competitiveness. 
