<HEADLINE> Scientists Call for Urgent Action to Save Oceans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,600 marine
scientists from 65 countries today unanimously called for urgent
action to save the world's oceans from severe damage by human
activity.
</P>
<P>
They said quick action must be taken to combat overfishing,
pollution and coastal development in a joint petition introduced
here today at the U.S. Capitol by the Marine Conservation Biology
Institute.
</P>
<P>
"The sea is in real trouble, much more trouble than we
previously thought," said Elliot Norse, director of the institute,
at a news conference at the Capitol. "We must act now, not 20
years from now or 10 years from now if we are to prevent further
degradation of the marine environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the United Nations's International Year of the
Ocean, the scientists said in their petition entitled Troubled
Waters: A Call for Action that the destruction of marine
biological diversity from five causes: over-exploitation of
species; physical alteration of ecosystems; pollution; alien
species from distant waters disrupting local food webs; and global
atmospheric change.
</P>
<P>
They urged the world's governments and even individuals to take
measures including launching education to protect the oceans where
live 99 percent of the world's 30 million species, with less than
1 percent on land or in fresh water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
