<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen to take 11-day Visit to Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon announced on
Tuesday that Defense Secretary William Cohen will visit China and
six other countries in Asia from Jan. 12 through 22.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's trip to Asia was originally scheduled in last November
but was postponed because of a weapons inspection crisis in Iraq.
But Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon in announcing the upcoming trip
said the situation in Iraq had "changed dramatically" since
November as Baghdad had allowed expelled American inspectors back
and the weapons inspections had been resumed.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said Cohen will fly first to Malaysia and then to
Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand, China, Japan and South Korea to
discuss bilateral and regional security interests.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to China on Jan. 17-20, Cohen and Chinese
defense officials will sign a maritime consultation agreement
aimed at reducing the risk of naval incidents at sea between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He will also discussed with China's Defense Minister Chi
Haotian the implementation of modest steps to boost U.S.-China
military-to-military ties, including increased exchanges of armed
forced personnel, following last October's Washington summit
between President Jiang Zemin and President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said Cohen planned chiefly to discuss military and
strategic issues with leaders of all the countries he is to visit,
but economic problems were likely to come up, including a
suddenly-reduced ability by Asian countries to purchase arms.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has recently announced it would delay the planned $392
million purchase of eight Boeing-built F-18 fighter jets for up to
three years. The deal was originally scheduled to be completed by
2000.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Defense Minister Kim Dong-jin said during his
visit to Washington in December that his government might also
be forced to delay foreign arms purchases because of a economic
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
