<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Considering WFP Fresh Food Appeal for DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
considering new food aid to the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) in response to a fresh appeal from the U.N. World
Food Program (WFP), the State Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will carefully examine this appeal, and the United States
intends to consult with other countries," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The food aid appeal recently made by the WFP was said to differ
from earlier ones in its size, the number of beneficiaries and the
length of time covered.
</P>
<P>
The amount requested is nearly double the total 1997 appeal.
The people to be aided will reach 7.5 million, as opposed to last
year's 4.7 million. And the length of time will cover a 12-month
period, rather than for the immediate needs as it has been in the
past. In short, the WFP says it needs 658,000 metric tons of food,
valued at 979 million US dollars, to help DPRK people from famine
in the upcoming year.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States has "always responded positively
to previous humanitarian appeals" from the WFP for the assistance
to the DPRK people. But he said with the increase of food
distributions the number of monitors should also be doubled.
Monitoring and distribution of aid are said to have been a
constant concern of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Rubin, however, said the monitoring will not be a concern
since Pyongyang has agreed to double the number of U.N. monitors
to 48. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980107.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Calls for Karadzich Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 should be one in
which former Bosnian Serb President Radovan Karadzich, who has
been charged with a war criminal by the Hague Tribunal, is finally
extradited to the Hague to answer war crime charges, said German
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel this morning.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Hina, the Croatian News Agency, Kinkel
told the media in Leipzig that he wanted to see a more robust
international mandate in Bosnia and that he was confident that
Karadzich would be called to account this year.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is also seeking Karadzich's arrest this
year. UN spokesman in Sarajevo Aleksandar Ivanko said Monday that
1998 would be the year when indicted war crimes suspects in Bosnia
would be arrested.
</P>
<P>
He told the media that the Hague Tribunal was determined to
seek bigger fish, people who had been commanders during the war or
who had belonged to the management structure.
</P>
<P>
Ivanko added that Karadzich's home address in Pale was well
known and that the international police force had seen him there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
