<HEADLINE> German Carmaker Facing Possible Punishment by EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, is expected to punish the
German carmaker Volkswagen once more for allegedly playing foul.
</P>
<P>
This might well be another time when the commission goes for
the carmaker after it settled a damaging row with Germany over
illegal subsidies paid to Volkswagen two months ago, a commission
source said here today.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen is accused of banning its dealerships from selling
to residents of other countries trying to take advantage of
different national prices and taxes.
</P>
<P>
Similar complaints were heard for the first time in 1995 when
residents from Germany, Austria and France said they had been
refused a car from Volkswagen or its sister company Audi from
their Italian distributor called Autogerma.
</P>
<P>
German car buyers had reportedly met the same problem more
recently in Denmark and the Netherlands, where the price of cars
before tax could be up to 30 percent cheaper than in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The commission source said it was likely that the EU executive
would make a decision on the Italian case in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen could face fines or periodic penalty payments if it
does not change its present business policy. But the commission
source declined to give any details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
