<HEADLINE> UK Likely to Propose EU Mission to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook, whose country is holding the current European Union (EU)
Presidency, said Tuesday that there might be a EU ministeral visit
to Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Cook expressed grave concern in the reported massive killings
in Algeria by saying: "Not only is the death toll appallingly
high, but the manner of the deaths is particularly distressing."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 500 Algerian civilians have been
killed in the first six days of the holy Moslem month of Ramandan
and the Armed Islamic Group was likely to be blamed for most of
those killings.
</P>
<P>
Cook note that Britain, as current EU President, would put the
issue on the agenda of the EU Foreign Affairs Council meeting to
be held on January 26.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary stressed that the meeting would also
consider whether a EU delegation should visit Algeria to assess
the situation there.
</P>
<P>
"We are exploring with our partners the possibility of a troika
mission," Cook said. The so-called troika delegation includes the
current, the immediate past and the next EU presidency state.
</P>
</TEXT>
