<HEADLINE> European Shares Mainly Down on Weak Dow, Asian Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major stock markets
in Europe suspended their recent rally and ended weaker today,
with London being the only one that managed to close 1.9 points
higher.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index managed to recover from a loss of 40
points earlier in the day and ended on a slightly firmer note as
the index shook off a bout of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that Wall Street weakness, losses in Asia and soft
oil prices were all key factors which kept the market subdued.
</P>
<P>
The index ended higher for the six session in a run, at 5,264.4
points, up 1.9 points, as rising gilts and benign inflation
prospects offered some support.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt closed weaker as the market
consolidated in the wake of a two-day rally. The DAX-30 index fell
by 32.18 points to end at 4,352.63.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the German Institute for Economic Research forecast
unemployment would rise to 4.5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris dropped by 35.11 points to finish at
3,037.73.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking was the main influence of the session, along with
weakness in Asian markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
