<HEADLINE> EU Begins Investigating Alleged Polish Twine Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body, the European Commission, said here today that it
had started probing into allegations that Polish-made
polypropylene binder or baler twine was being dumped in EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that a trade association, the EU Twine,
Cordage and Netting Industries (Eurocord), had filed a complaint
with the EU executive on behalf of producers across EU countries.
</P>
<P>
In a notice published in the EU's Official Journal, the
Commission said the allegation of dumping was based on a
comparison of domestic prices in Poland with export prices to the
EU, adding that the dumping margins calculated on the basis were
"significant".
</P>
<P>
The EU producers alleged hat the volume and prices of the
imported twine, used by farmers to bind bundles to be picked up by
automatic balers, had had a "substantial adverse effect on the
financial situation" of EU industry, according to the Commission.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive has decided to give concerned parties 40 days
to submit relevant information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
