<HEADLINE> EU Should Urge Turkey to Act on Kurd Influx: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
commissioner today urged the EU to ask Turkey to take measures to
stem a flood of Kurd refugees into the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, EU commissioner for external relations with
central and eastern European countries, made the appeal at a
meeting of the European Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee
held on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He told the committee that the EU should have to consider
tightening controls at its own outer borders to prevent mafia
smugglers of people taking advantage of the Kurds' plight.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's necessary that we consult with Turkey to see
what, from their side, can be done to stop a completely
uncontrolled influx of immigrants," the commissioner was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Kurdish people arrived last week in Italy
aboard two boats from Turkey. More are said to be still on the
way. The arrival has caused fears among EU member countries,
especially Italy's EU neighbors, of an influx of illegal
immigrants through Italy.
</P>
<P>
EU experts who deal with the Schengen passport-free travel zone
involving a total of nine EU countries at present, are scheduled
to meet on Wednesday to discuss this matter.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said the experts would discuss whether the EU's
external border controls were an effective protection against
organized criminals dealing in illegal immigration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
