<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Name Riel Father of Confederation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is to
name Metis leader Louis Riel a Father of Confederation as part of
reconciliation to the Aboriginal Peoples.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to be released Wednesday, the government will
recognize the contribution of Indians, Metis and Inuit peoples to
the founding of Canada.
</P>
<P>
It will also single out Riel for his role in establishing the
province of Manitoba, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
Riel, who was hanged for treason in Regina in 1885 after the
Northwest Rebellion, is a controversial figure in Canada and his
death has been a cause of division between French and English
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming reconciliation statement will see Riel take
another step toward having his conviction lifted by Canada's
Parliament, according to Metis leaders.
</P>
<P>
Gerald Morin, leader of the Metis National Council, said the
statement may be tantamount to an apology for the treatment of
Riel.
</P>
<P>
"If you read between the lines, a Father of Confederation
cannot be guilty of treason," Morin was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
